column58: No change to previous policy.  Regions for Long Term Care moving to Green Alert continue to allow for general visitation, group activities and passes out of facility.  On November 28, LTC in Yellowknife moved to Green Alert Level.   On December 1, LTC and Charlotte Venus Home facilities in Inuvik have moved to Green Alert Level.  All other long term care facilities in Hay River, Behchoko, Norman Wells, Fort Simpson, Fort Smith, and at Stanton remain at Green Alert Level. This has allowed for increased visitation, group programing and passes out of facility for residents.    Other measures under the LTC Green Alert Level includes:  - active screening for both staff and residents;  - recommendations to staff to only work at one facility;  - visitors require continuous masking and will be asked to show proof of full vaccination status (2-doses).    https://web.archive.org/web/20211206041438/https://www.nthssa.ca/en/newsroom/public-notice-%E2%80%93-updates-alert-levels-long-term-care-facilities  https://web.archive.org/web/20211206042133/https://www.hss.gov.nt.ca/professionals/sites/professionals/files/resources/management-policy-long-term-care-facilities.pdf

column34: Jan 12, 2022: Today, the Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Finance, the Honourable Chrystia Freeland, and the Minister of International Trade, Export Promotion, Small Business and Economic Development, the Honourable Mary Ng, announced that the repayment deadline for CEBA loans to qualify for partial loan forgiveness is being extended from December 31, 2022, to December 31, 2023, for all eligible borrowers in good standing.    This extension will support short-term economic recovery and offer greater repayment flexibility to small businesses and not-for-profit organizations, many of which are facing continued challenges due to the pandemic. Repayment on or before the new deadline of December 31, 2023, will result in loan forgiveness of up to a third of the value of the loans (meaning up to $20,000).    Outstanding loans would subsequently convert to two-year term loans with interest of 5 per cent per annum commencing on January 1, 2024, with the loans fully due by December 31, 2025.    The government is also announcing that the repayment deadline to qualify for partial forgiveness for CEBA-equivalent lending through the Regional Relief and Recovery Fund is extended to December 31, 2023.    https://archive.vn/YsBQ9

column9: All public schools will remain closed until at least 17 Jan 2022:     The Back to School Guidance for January 2022 includes public health measures to minimize risk and disruption and increase safety in schools when students and staff return to in-class learning.     Some measures contained in the CPHO Back to School Guidance for 2022 include:    Masks will be required for all students, teachers and visitors in all indoor areas; children and staff should have access to a good quality three-layer mask.  Prior to resuming class all students and staff members will be asked to take two rapid antigen screening tests, 48 hours apart; students will be tested up to three (3) times per week during the first few weeks of school.  Students and staff must complete daily home active screening for symptoms and should not attend school if they are not feeling well or have symptoms of COVID-19.  Where possible, schools should implement cohorting of students and staff, and cohorts should be 50 or less; cohorting is not required in grades 10-12.  Portable air filters are recommended in classrooms that lack mechanical ventilation.  Physical distancing is recommended in all areas, including staff rooms; students are encouraged to select a small, consistent group of friends to associate with in school and on buses.  All students and staff eligible for vaccination should be fully immunized.  The Department of Education and Lifelong Learning is working with the educational authorities to ensure all of the Back to School Guidance from the CPHO is implemented prior to the return to in-class learning.     175 new portable HEPA filters have been purchased and are being delivered this week to schools that currently rely on natural ventilation. Every classroom and high use area within these 10 schools will be fitted with one of the portable ventilation units. Work is also ongoing to ensure the current mechanical systems are maintained and working efficiently, based on industry standards.    Over the next two weeks all excess furniture will be removed from classrooms to give more space for physical distancing, and 30,000 three-layer reusable masks will be delivered to schools for students and staff before the return to in-class learning.    https://archive.vn/VgKk1
column15: the previously announced restrictions remain in place until at least 17 Jan 2022:     The extended public health measures include:     Personal gatherings limited to 10 steady contacts plus household, the smaller the better.  Wedding receptions and funeral receptions and wakes/visitation are not permitted.  All organized gatherings (including worship services, theatres, wedding and funeral ceremonies and concerts) must operate with a maximum of 50 people with physical distancing between households. Multiple cohorts are not permitted.  Gyms, fitness facilities and retail can continue to operate up to 50 per cent capacity with physical distancing and masks.  Visitation to long term and community care is limited to three partners in care plus three designated visitors with physical distancing.   Physical distancing is required in all venues up to a maximum of 50 per cent capacity in retail businesses and vax pass events (including theatres, gyms, community gatherings, casinos, etc.).   Restaurants and eating establishments must maintain six feet distance between tables with a maximum table size of 10 people. Proof of vaccine is required for all patron and masking is required at all times except when eating or drinking. Food premises and eating establishments must stop food and beverage service at approximately 11:00 pm and close by midnight.  No dancing at events and no karaoke.  Indoor sport and recreational activities continue to be paused for Island children under the age of 12 years, including organized sports, tournaments, competitions, games, team training and practices.  League play and practices for individuals over the age of 12 are paused.   Whenever possible, employers should support employees to work from home.        https://archive.vn/PrY8Q

column9: 3 January 2022 is the first day on the elementary and secondary public school calendar after the holiday break in some Canadian jurisdictions. However, school re-opening has been delayed in many jurisdictions. In Quebec, the Premier announced that “schools, junior colleges and universities won’t reopen to in-person classes until at least Jan. 17.” This provincial government order applies to all Quebec post-secondary institutions in contrast to other jurisdictions, where vaccination/testing mandates or decisions to offer most classes online are policies set by individual post-secondary institutions rather than dictated by governments. See University Affairs Canada, Toronto Star newspaper and CTV news websites archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101212353/https://www.thestar.com/politics/2021/12/30/quebecs-premier-to-hold-covid-19-briefing-this-evening-amid-rapid-rise-in-cases.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220103002127/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/growing-number-of-provinces-delay-return-to-school-amid-omicron-surge-1.5722936  https://web.archive.org/web/20211213193256/https://www.universityaffairs.ca/news/news-article/covid-19-updates-for-canadas-universities/
column12: On 3 January 2022, non-essential businesses remain closed in Nunavut Territory. In the rest of Canada, businesses are open with varying levels of restrictions. Many jurisdictions restrict access to some non-essential businesses to fully vaccinated customers (or require proof of a recent negative test). See Retail Council of Canada and government of Nunavut websites, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211225214240/https://gov.nu.ca/health/news/new-covid-cases-lead-nunavut-wide-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20211225215037/https://www.retailcouncil.org/coronavirus-info-for-retailers/vaccination-requirements-by-province/
column15: On 3 January 2022, public events such as ice hockey matches are restricted with spectators banned or numbers limited in most of Canada. The province of Saskatchewan allows spectators, who must show proof of fully vaccinated or negative-testing status. The Province of Alberta follows that approach, but  provides an opt-out: “Indoor facilities that do not implement the Restrictions Exemption Program [vaccination/test mandate] must follow these restrictions: Capacity limited to 1/3 fire code occupancy. Attendees must be with household members only, or 2 close contacts if they live alone.” Public New Year’s Eve celebrations were cancelled in most of Canada. See CTV news and Alberta government websites, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20220102131939/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/holiday-season-covid-19-restrictions-by-province-and-territory-1.5712593  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217153414/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-public-health-actions.aspx
column18: On 3 January 2022, the Government of Canada notes: “Public health advice across Canada varies widely due to local situations, which are rapidly changing. It’s important that you: continue to follow the recommendations and restrictions of your local public health authority, including gathering size limits”. Most provinces and territories limit private gatherings – e.g., in Quebec “beginning Friday [31 Dec. 2021] … indoor private gatherings will be banned”, Ontario: “Starting Dec. 19, private social gatherings are limited to 10 people indoors and 25 people outdoors.” Nova Scotia: “As of Dec. 22, informal gatherings, both indoors and outdoors, will be limited to 10 people from the same household or social group.” Manitoba: “As of Dec. 21 and lasting until Jan. 11, private indoor gatherings are limited to 10 guests if everyone is fully vaccinated. If there are any unvaccinated people, the limit is five guests.” Northwest Territories: “25 people can gather in households if everyone, except children under the age of 12, is fully vaccinated. The number falls to 10 people if not everyone is fully vaccinated.”  However, in the province of Saskatchewan: ‘Premier Scott Moe said … there will be no gathering restrictions or other public measures coming to the province at this time…: “we’re in a better position right now than other provinces,” [Health Minister] said’. See CTV and Global news, Toronto Star newspaper and government of Canada websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220102131728/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/prevention-risks/private-indoor-gatherings.html   https://web.archive.org/web/20220101212353/https://www.thestar.com/politics/2021/12/30/quebecs-premier-to-hold-covid-19-briefing-this-evening-amid-rapid-rise-in-cases.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220102131939/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/holiday-season-covid-19-restrictions-by-province-and-territory-1.5712593  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101215649/https://globalnews.ca/news/8480130/covid-19-saskatchewan-update-dec-30-scott-moe-paul-merriman/

column32: On 3 January 2022, the government of Canada continues with the policy of replacing the Canada Recovery Benefit (CRB) for self-employed Canadians who lost income with “the new Canada Worker Lockdown Benefit that would provide $300 a week to eligible workers who are unable to work due to a temporary local lockdown anytime between October 24, 2021 and May 7, 2022...Eligible workers would include those who are ineligible for Employment insurance.” However, there are “conditions [on] benefit payments … none can go to workers who lose work or hours because they have refused to get vaccinated. The [conditional] rules don’t apply to those who have a medical exemption.” See Government of Canada website, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217144134/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20210917191252/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/recovery-benefit/crb-who-apply.html
column34: On 3 Jan. 2022, government of Canada support continues: “To help students and young Canadians who have been particularly hard-hit by COVID-19, we are waiving the interest for full-time and part-time students on the federal portion of Canada Student Loans and Canada Apprentice Loans until March 31, 2023.” See Government of Canada website, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217144134/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html
column41: On 3 Jan. 2022, the government of Canada continues with a “national public education campaign that provides Canadians with evidence-based information on COVID-19, and encourages behaviours that protect individuals and our communities. This campaign includes advertising, partnerships, social marketing, social media posts, information resources, targeted outreach to at-risk populations.” See Government of Canada website, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217144501/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/canadas-reponse.html
column43: On 3 Jan. 2021, the policy intent of some jurisdictions continues to be to supplement polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing of symptomatic cases with mass availability of lateral flow and other rapid tests to asymptomatic individuals. However, in many parts of Canada, the caseload wave is frustrating efforts to achieve testing goals: “Officials across the country have also warned that recent case counts are an underestimate because testing systems are overwhelmed and people are being asked to forgo lab testing all together if they are young and have mild symptoms.” Canada’s most populous province, Ontario “currently has a limited supply of rapid antigen tests …Right now we need them to protect our workplaces in long-term care, in cancer wards, in transplant centres …Ontario won’t be in a position to hand out new shipments of kits to the public until late January, at earliest,” the province’s Chief Medical Officer of Health, said in a news conference … [and] later told the CP24 news channel…Officials in Ontario and elsewhere have started restricting the public’s access to polymerase chain reaction (or PCR) testing ... Positive results from rapid-test kits are not reported in official COVID-19 case counts.’ See Globe and Mail newspaper website, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20211228170831/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-canadas-covid-19-cases-top-two-million-as-hospitals-brace-for-unknowns/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101210221/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-supply-crunch-coming-as-demand-for-covid-19-rapid-testing-soars/
column45: On 3 Jan. 2022, government of Canada advises that when individuals “test positive for COVID-19, a public health official will ask you questions to collect important information about your symptoms; activities and travel you did before you tested positive; all the people you may have been in close contact with while you were contagious ...contact tracing. It's a key public health measure.” Most provinces and territories intend to apply this advice, if conditions and resources permit. However, tracing capacity is not sufficient in many jurisdictions to deal with a surge in cases; most recent e.g.: “Nova Scotia … Public health says it is prioritizing contact tracing in long-term care and health-care facilities, as well as correctional facilities, shelters and other congregate settings.” “Omicron’s sheer transmissibility has already swamped resources for testing and tracing in some parts of the country, a problem that is expected to grow worse.” See Governments of Canada and Globe and Mail newspaper websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217144749/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/symptoms/testing.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20211221124402/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-provinces-ramp-up-covid-19-boosters-as-they-try-to-head-off-omicron/
column52: On 3 jan. 2022, all provinces and territories continue to require masks in indoor public spaces consistent with Government of Canada advice: “a vaccines plus approach continues to be essential to the pandemic response in Canada. This includes … properly wearing a well-fitted and well-constructed face mask when in public or private spaces with others outside of your immediate household”. See Governments of Canada, CTV news and RCC websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220102131939/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/holiday-season-covid-19-restrictions-by-province-and-territory-1.5712593  https://web.archive.org/web/20211227131740/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2021/12/statement-from-the-chief-public-health-officer-of-canada-on-december-23-2021.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217145838/https://www.retailcouncil.org/coronavirus-info-for-retailers/mask-requirements-affecting-retailers/
column58: On 3 january 2022, provincial and territorial governments continue to be responsible for regulating long-term care (LTC) homes with the government of Canada providing guidance to protect residents and staff from covid-19. Some provinces and territories have restricted all visitors. Most provinces and territories restrict less-than-fully vaccinated persons from visiting LTC homes and some jurisdictions require LTC staff to be fully vaccinated or regularly show negative tests. Yukon Territory appears to have the fewest restrictions. See British Columbia, Yukon, Manitoba government websites websites (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):   https://web.archive.org/web/20211213222911/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/long-term-care-visitation-guidelines-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20211203154523/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-professionals/clinical-resources/covid-19-care/clinical-care/long-term-care-facilities-assisted-living  https://web.archive.org/web/20211203154611/https://sharedhealthmb.ca/files/covid-19-pch-vaccinated.pdf
column62: As of 3 january 2022, eligibility continues to be 5 years of age and up in all provinces and territories consistent with national government guidance. Provinces and territories have designated long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, those aged 50 and up, recipients of two earlier AZ doses as eligible for third doses based on national government guidance. In addition: “NACI [National Advisory Committee on Immunization] recommends that a booster dose of an authorized mRNA COVID-19 vaccine may be offered =6 months after completion of a primary COVID-19 vaccine series to adults 18- 49 years of age with consideration of jurisdictional and individual risks.” See government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20211203160713/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses.pdf
column64: On 3 Jan. 2022, availability is 5 years of age and up in all provinces and territories consistent with national government guidance. Vaccinations for those aged 5-11 have just started over the past several weeks. Based on national government guidance, provinces and territories are also delivering third doses to long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, those aged 18 and up and recipients of two earlier AstraZeneca (AZ) doses. (AZ no longer used in Canada.) Data up to 18 december 2021 collected by the Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC) show 39.5% of Canadians aged 5-11 have received at least one dose, 87% aged 12-39, rising steadily by age group to >95% aged 70+ with 1% of those aged 5-11 fully vaccinated, 83% of those aged 12-39, rising to 95% aged 70+. See government of Canada and CTV news websites, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211203160713/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses.pdf
column72: On 3 Jan. 2022: “Free vaccines will be available to everyone in Canada.” See government of Canada website, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20211217150658/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html

column9: On 7 January 2022: “All provinces except Saskatchewan have extended the [elementary and secondary public school] holiday break or moved students to virtual learning”. In Quebec, the Premier announced that “schools, junior colleges and universities won’t reopen to in-person classes until at least Jan. 17.” This provincial government order applies to all Quebec post-secondary institutions in contrast to other jurisdictions, where vaccination/testing mandates or decisions to offer most classes online are policies set by individual post-secondary institutions rather than dictated by governments. See University Affairs Canada, Toronto Star and Globe and Mail newspaper websites archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107130518/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-ontario-to-fast-track-covid-19-booster-shots-for-education-and-child/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101212353/https://www.thestar.com/politics/2021/12/30/quebecs-premier-to-hold-covid-19-briefing-this-evening-amid-rapid-rise-in-cases.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20211213193256/https://www.universityaffairs.ca/news/news-article/covid-19-updates-for-canadas-universities/
column12: On 7 January 2022, non-essential businesses remain closed in Nunavut Territory. “Nunavut’s Minister of Health, John Main, has extended the territory’s public health emergency until January 20, 2022. All existing measures under the public health emergency order remain in effect.” In the rest of Canada, businesses are open with varying levels of restrictions. Many jurisdictions restrict access to some non-essential businesses to fully vaccinated customers (or require proof of a recent negative test). See Retail Council of Canada and government of Nunavut websites, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107140536/https://www.retailcouncil.org/coronavirus-info-for-retailers/vaccination-requirements-by-province/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107141016/https://www.gov.nu.ca/health/news/nunavut-extends-public-health-emergency-33  https://web.archive.org/web/20211225214240/https://gov.nu.ca/health/news/new-covid-cases-lead-nunavut-wide-restrictions
column15: On 7 January 2022, in Canada’s most populous province Ontario: “Organized public events will be limited to five people indoors. Indoor meeting and event spaces must be closed with some exceptions, but outdoor spaces can open with restrictions.” In most of Canada, those events, that are open, only allow spectators, who show proof of fully vaccinated or negative-testing status. The Province of Alberta follows that approach, but  provides an opt-out: “Indoor facilities that do not implement the Restrictions Exemption Program [vaccination/test mandate] must follow these restrictions: Limit capacity to 1/3 fire code occupancy. Require attendees to be with household members only, or 2 close contacts if they live alone.” Professional ice hockey “Winnipeg Jets … team has announced it won't be moving home games out of its home province after all. SaskTel executive director Scott Ford told CBC News said the Jets had been considering the centre as a potential venue…While Manitoba currently limits attendance at professional sports or concert events at either 50 per cent capacity or 250 people, whichever is less, Saskatchewan has no capacity restrictions.  Both provinces require proof of immunization to enter major arenas.” See CBC news,  Retail Council of Canada and Alberta government websites, archived :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107142338/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-public-health-actions.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107140536/https://www.retailcouncil.org/coronavirus-info-for-retailers/vaccination-requirements-by-province/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107142112/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-ont-quicklist-1.6302972  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107181639/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/sasktel-centre-winnipeg-jets-1.6307120
column18: On 7 January 2022, the Government of Canada notes: “Public health advice across Canada varies widely due to local situations, which are rapidly changing. It’s important that you: continue to follow the recommendations and restrictions of your local public health authority, including gathering size limits”. Most provinces and territories limit private gatherings – e.g., in Quebec “beginning Friday [31 Dec. 2021] … indoor private gatherings will be banned”, Ontario: “Social gathering will be limited to five people indoors and 10 people outdoors.” However, in Saskatchewan: “The province is still not implementing official gathering restrictions, as other provinces have done, despite skyrocketing COVID-19 case numbers. Meanwhile, videos allegedly showing high school students partying mask-less and in close quarters on New Year's Eve, as well videos of adults at nightclubs, are being shared across social media … In a statement to the CBC, the province said it would not be bringing in gathering limits”. See CBC news, Toronto Star newspaper and government of Canada websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107142949/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/prevention-risks/private-indoor-gatherings.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107142112/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/covid-ont-quicklist-1.6302972  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101212353/https://www.thestar.com/politics/2021/12/30/quebecs-premier-to-hold-covid-19-briefing-this-evening-amid-rapid-rise-in-cases.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107143454/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/do-not-have-gatherings-top-doctor-says-limit-contacts-1.6306370
column21: On 7 january 2022: “Isolation due to surging cases of the Omicron variant was also putting pressure on some … transit … services…Winnipeg Transit … said some routes would still be affected. “Unfortunately, we have not been able to cover all shifts. To mitigate impact to the overall service, we’ve had to cancel some runs … GO Transit ...The regional transit agency serving the Greater Toronto and Hamilton region says a temporary reduction in train and bus service is set to begin …frontline teams are averaging 20 to 30 per cent fewer staff each day because of illness or isolation, and that rate is expected to rise over the next few weeks. The agency says the service reductions will be temporary.” These reductions arrive on top of    earlier service reductions that were an unintended consequence of a vaccination mandate at the City of Toronto transit agency, Greater Toronto Area commuter trains and buses as well as City of Hamilton buses. In St. John’s, Newfoundland, transit bus seating capacity has been reduced as a covid safety measure. See St. John’s Metrobus as well as Globe and Mail, CBC, CP24, Toronto Star and Hamilton Spectator news websites, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220105141818/https://www.metrobus.com/covid19/html/schedules/index.asp  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107160746/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-staffing-challenges-from-surging-covid-19-cases-affecting-some-police/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107162248/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/go-transit-covid-cancellations-1.6305036  https://web.archive.org/web/20220102210050/https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2021/12/27/an-inside-look-at-how-the-covid-19-vaccine-mandate-became-the-breaking-point-for-the-ttcs-largest-union.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20211211133320/https://www.cp24.com/news/up-to-three-per-cent-of-go-train-trips-could-be-cancelled-as-vaccine-mandate-takes-effect-for-alstom-employees-1.5695102  https://web.archive.org/web/20211115151856/https://www.thespec.com/news/hamilton-region/2021/11/12/vaccine-mandate-city-workers.html
column24: On 7 Jan. 2022, the overnight curfew continues in the province of Quebec: “curfew exceptions include essential workers, pharmacy visits, dog walkers”.  See Montreal Gazette newspaper website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107155929/https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/covid-19-updates-january-7-montreal-quebec-new-cases-vaccine-lockdown-curfew-legault
column27: On 7 january 2022, the government of Canada continues to require all passengers “Boarding flights and trains …12 years of age plus 4 months, or older you’ll need to be fully vaccinated”. Some Canadian jurisdictions continue with rules restricting non-essential visits by non-residents – e.g., fully vaccinated (two doses) visitors only and/or quarantine requirements. See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107145520/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/domestic-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107145622/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/provinces
column29: On 7 January 2022, Canada remains open to entry by non-citizens, but only those who meet the following requirements: “you can enter Canada if you qualify as a fully vaccinated traveller or you’re coming for a non-optional purpose”. See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107155555/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/visitors-workers-students
column32: On 7 January 2022, the government of Canada continues: “The Canada Worker Lockdown Benefit provides $300 a week to eligible workers who are unable to work due to a temporary local lockdown anytime between October 24, 2021 and May 7, 2022. The benefit is only available when a COVID-19 lockdown order is designated for your region.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107162555/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html
column34: On 7 Jan. 2022, government of Canada support continues: “To help students and young Canadians who have been particularly hard-hit by COVID-19, we are waiving the interest for full-time and part-time students on the federal portion of Canada Student Loans and Canada Apprentice Loans until March 31, 2023.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107162555/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html
column41: On 7 Jan. 2022, the government of Canada continues with a “national public education campaign that provides Canadians with evidence-based information on COVID-19, and encourages behaviours that protect individuals and our communities. This campaign includes advertising, partnerships, social marketing, social media posts, information resources, targeted outreach to at-risk populations.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107164403/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/canadas-reponse.html
column43: On 7 Jan. 2021, the policy intent of some jurisdictions continues to be to supplement polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing of symptomatic cases with mass availability of lateral flow and other rapid tests to asymptomatic individuals. However, in many parts of Canada, the caseload wave is frustrating efforts to achieve testing aspirations: ‘rising case numbers have made polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests more difficult to access…Ontario, which has procured millions of rapid tests on its own, intended to use the new ones from Ottawa in “settings like hospitals, home and community care, long-term care and retirement homes, as well as child care centres and schools, so they can continue operating safely…Quebec …Before Christmas, the provincial government allotted five free rapid tests for every person 14 years and up, given out through pharmacies, but supplies quickly ran out. New Brunswick announced … it would begin restricting access to rapid tests after pronounced shortages. People now must register online and book an appointment to pick up a rapid-test kit at a local assessment centre. Lab-based PCR tests in that province will be reserved for symptomatic people at the highest risk of being hospitalized owing to COVID-19’. See Globe and Mail newspaper website, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220106165002/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-additional-140-million-covid-19-rapid-tests-to-be-delivered-to/
column45: On 7 Jan. 2022, government of Canada advises that when individuals “test positive for COVID-19, a public health official will ask you questions to collect important information about your symptoms; activities and travel you did before you tested positive; all the people you may have been in close contact with while you were contagious ...contact tracing. It's a key public health measure.” Most provinces and territories intend to apply this advice, if conditions and resources permit. However, tracing capacity is not sufficient in many jurisdictions to deal with a surge in cases; most recent e.g.: “contact tracing isn't going to be effective in B.C. anymore, [Provincial Health Officer] said. People who test positive or suspect they have COVID-19 are being asked to proactively let their contacts know they might have been exposed.” See Government of Canada and CBC news websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106170721/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/symptoms/testing.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106170619/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/covid-19-update-bc-jan-4-2022-1.6303907
column52: On 7 jan. 2022, all provinces and territories continue to require masks in indoor public spaces consistent with Government of Canada advice: “a vaccines plus approach continues to be essential to the pandemic response in Canada. This includes … properly wearing a well-fitted and well-constructed face mask when in public or private spaces with others outside of your immediate household”. See Government of Canada and McCarthly Law websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107165853/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-recovery-and-re-opening-tracker  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107182229/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2021/12/statement-from-the-chief-public-health-officer-of-canada-on-december-30-2021.html
column55: On 7 Jan. 2022 10:16AM EST, according to the CTV news unofficial vaccine tracker, 31,556,414 Canadians (82.5% of the total national population and 87% of the vaccine-eligible population aged 5+) have received at least one dose of an approved COVID-19 vaccine -- Moderna, Pfizer, Johnson & Johnson (J&J) Janssen, or AstraZeneca (AZ no longer recommended except in limited circumstances). 29,488,558 Canadians (77% of total pop. and 81% of vax-eligible aged 5+) have received two doses. All provinces and territories are making vaccinations available to residents aged 5 and up. Vaccinations for those aged 5-11 started at end-November 2021. Provinces and territories are also delivering third doses to long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, senior citizens and recipients of two earlier AZ doses based on national government guidance. The Government-of-Canada-recommended age for third doses has been lowered to those aged 50 and up and to age 18+ where local circumstances warrant. 9,222,470 third doses have been administered, or 24% of the national population. Some provinces have started delivering fourth doses. (Note that vaccination data do not include Canadians who returned home after being vaccinated in other countries while wintering at retirement homes or on essential business trips. On the other hand, there may be a small amount of double-counting when residents live and work in different provinces, vaccinations took place at work and both provinces count the vaccinations.) “Free vaccines will be available to everyone in Canada.” See government of Canada and CTV news websites, archived :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107184500/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107190826/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/summary.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107184833/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-booster-eligibility-by-province-and-territory-in-canada
column58: On 7 january 2022, provincial and territorial governments continue to be responsible for regulating long-term care (LTC) homes with the government of Canada providing guidance to protect residents and staff from covid-19. Some provinces and territories have restricted visitors. Most provinces and territories restrict less-than-fully vaccinated persons from visiting LTC homes and some jurisdictions require LTC staff to be fully vaccinated or regularly show negative tests. E.g., in Ontario: “As of December 13, 2021, all staff had to be fully vaccinated to work in long-term care homes, unless they have a valid medical exemption. Visitors will also have to provide proof of all three doses in order to enter a long-term care home once the temporary pause on general visitors is lifted… the province announced it would be banning general visitors in long-term care and will be prohibiting residents from leaving on day absences for social purposes. Two designated caregivers per person may continue to enter the home.” See Yukon government and CTV news websites:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220107182515/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/long-term-care-visitation-guidelines-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107183346/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-offering-fourth-covid-19-vaccine-dose-to-long-term-care-residents-mandating-booster-for-staff-1.5723637
column62: As of 7 january 2022, eligibility continues to be 5 years of age and up in all provinces and territories consistent with national government guidance. Provinces and territories have designated long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, those aged 50 and up, recipients of two earlier AZ doses as eligible for third doses based on national government guidance. In addition: “NACI [National Advisory Committee on Immunization] recommends that a [third] booster dose of an authorized mRNA COVID-19 vaccine may be offered =6 months after completion of a primary COVID-19 vaccine series to adults 18- 49 years of age with consideration of jurisdictional and individual risks…Adults who are moderately to severely immunocompromised who have received a three-dose primary series are included in those who may receive a booster dose. Data on a fourth dose of a COVID-19 vaccine after the recommended three-dose primary series in this population is currently limited. These individuals may receive a booster at least 6 months after receiving their last dose.” See government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107190826/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/summary.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107184500/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107184833/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-booster-eligibility-by-province-and-territory-in-canada

column9: On 14 January 2022 in Canada at the elementary and secondary level: “Only schools in British Columbia, Alberta and Saskatchewan have opened their doors to in-person learning. Students in other provinces are learning online.” In Quebec: “The higher education ministry … sent a communication … to its establishments to confirm the return to in-person class, in accordance with public health recommendations, will take place as of January 17th, 2022,” ministry spokesperson … added that schools would be permitted a “transition period” and could delay their in-class returns to Jan. 31 at the latest.’ This provincial government order applies to all Quebec post-secondary institutions in contrast to most other jurisdictions, where vaccination/testing mandates or decisions to offer most classes online are policies set by individual post-secondary institutions rather than dictated by governments. See University Affairs Canada, University of New Brunswick, Global News and Globe and Mail newspaper websites archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111214106/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-schools-in-alberta-saskatchewan-facing-staff-shortages-due-to-rising/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111215017/https://globalnews.ca/news/8496876/quebec-cegeps-universities-bring-back-in-person-learning/  https://web.archive.org/web/20211213193256/https://www.universityaffairs.ca/news/news-article/covid-19-updates-for-canadas-universities/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113210148/https://www.unb.ca/coronavirus/community-updates/jan-13-22.html
column12: On 14 January 2022, non-essential businesses remain closed in Nunavut Territory. “Nunavut’s Minister of Health, John Main, has extended the territory’s public health emergency until January 20, 2022. All existing measures under the public health emergency order remain in effect.” In the rest of Canada, businesses are open with varying levels of restrictions. Many jurisdictions restrict access to some non-essential businesses to fully vaccinated customers (or require proof of a recent negative test). See Nunavut News, Globe and Mail newspaper and government of Nunavut websites, archived (and to be updated in future rounds when archive.org delays solved):  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113210434/https://www.nunavutnews.com/news/nunavut-ending-lockdown-jan-17/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107141016/https://www.gov.nu.ca/health/news/nunavut-extends-public-health-emergency-33  https://web.archive.org/web/20211225214240/https://gov.nu.ca/health/news/new-covid-cases-lead-nunavut-wide-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111210218/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/
column15: On 14 January 2022, in most of Canada organized public events such as concerts and sports matches are either banned, restricted to no spectators or only to those who show proof of vaccination. The Province of Alberta provides an opt-out: “Indoor facilities that do not implement the Restrictions Exemption Program [vaccination/test mandate] must follow these restrictions: Limit capacity to 1/3 fire code occupancy. Require attendees to be with household members only, or 2 close contacts if they live alone.” See Globe and Mail newspaper and Alberta government websites, archived :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111210218/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113170043/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-public-health-actions.aspx
column18: On 14 January 2022, the Government of Canada notes: “Public health advice across Canada varies widely due to local situations, which are rapidly changing. It’s important that you: continue to follow the recommendations and restrictions of your local public health authority, including gathering size limits”. Gathering limits range from tightest in Nunavut Territory – “Indoor gatherings are limited to single households, and bubbles of five others for emergencies. A maximum of five people are allowed at outdoor gatherings.” – to no limits: “There are no limits on indoor or outdoor gatherings in Saskatchewan… ‘We are asking Saskatchewan people to use their judgment when they do feel it is necessary to come together,’ [the Premier] said.” See Globe and Mail newspaper and government of Canada websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113165711/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/prevention-risks/private-indoor-gatherings.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113153916/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-saskatchewan-premier-scott-moe-to-not-interfere-with-restrictions-to/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111210218/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/
column21: On 14 january 2022 in Newfoundland and Labrador’s (NL’s) most populous city, St. John’s, transit is: “currently operating on a reduced schedule. Under provincial restrictions related to the COVID-19 pandemic, at Alert Level 3, a maximum of 19 passengers are permitted on board a bus at any one time.” In other regions: “southern Ontario commuters will find themselves with fewer options … as transit agency Metrolinx cuts back on service due to COVID-19… staffing levels are 20 to 30 per cent lower on average due to the rapid spread of COVID's Omicron variant…Metrolinx says it's decreasing service by about 15 per cent across the network.” These reductions arrive on top of earlier service reductions that were an unintended consequence of  vaccination mandates. “Ongoing staff shortages resulting from illness due to COVID-19, Metrolinx’s vaccine mandate … is cancelling service to and from Niagara Region …this weekend … January 8 and … 9”. In the City of Toronto: “The Toronto Transit Commission has fired 354 workers who did not comply with the transit agency's mandatory COVID-19 vaccination policy…Service changes made in November took the terminations into account”. See St. John’s Metrobus, Transit Toronto as well as Globe and Mail, CBC, and CTV news websites, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220112153630/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/go-transit-reduces-rail-bus-service-as-omicron-puts-pressure-on-ontario-workforce-1.5733755  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112153616/https://transittoronto.ca/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110122817/https://www.metrobus.com/covid19/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114012655/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ttc-firings-vaccination-policy-1.6310426
column24: On 14 Jan. 2022, an overnight curfew continues in the province of Quebec. ‘The Quebec government has said the province-wide curfew will be … lifted once the situation in hospitals improves … the province’s health minister …said. “We’ll re-evaluate what we are going to do for the 17th of January.”  See CTV news website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112152021/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/quebec-to-decide-whether-or-not-to-lift-curfew-next-week-dube-says-1.5734444
column27: On 14 january 2022, the government of Canada continues to require all passengers “Boarding flights and trains …12 years of age plus 4 months, or older you’ll need to be fully vaccinated”. Some Canadian jurisdictions continue with rules restricting non-essential visits by non-residents – e.g., fully vaccinated (two doses) visitors only and/or quarantine requirements. See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113165221/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/domestic-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113165257/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/provinces
column29: On 14 January 2022, Canada remains open to entry by non-citizens, but only those who meet the following requirements: “you can enter Canada if you qualify as a fully vaccinated traveller or you’re coming for a non-optional purpose”. See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113163702/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/visitors-workers-students
column32: On 14 January 2022, the government of Canada continues: “The Canada Worker Lockdown Benefit provides $300 a week to eligible workers who are unable to work due to a temporary local lockdown anytime between October 24, 2021 and May 7, 2022. The benefit is only available when a COVID-19 lockdown order is designated for your region.” All Canadians are eligible to receive this national government support when they live in a province, territory or regional health district that meets the definition of being in “lockdown”. See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162756/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html
column34: On 14 Jan. 2022, government of Canada support continues: “To help students and young Canadians who have been particularly hard-hit by COVID-19, we are waiving the interest for full-time and part-time students on the federal portion of Canada Student Loans and Canada Apprentice Loans until March 31, 2023.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162756/https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/economic-response-plan.html
column41: On 14 Jan. 2022, the government of Canada continues with a “national public education campaign that provides Canadians with evidence-based information on COVID-19, and encourages behaviours that protect individuals and our communities. This campaign includes advertising, partnerships, social marketing, social media posts, information resources, targeted outreach to at-risk populations.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162613/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/canadas-reponse.html
column43: On 14 Jan. 2021, the policy intent of some jurisdictions continues to be to supplement polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing of symptomatic cases with mass availability of lateral flow and other rapid tests to asymptomatic individuals. However, in many parts of Canada, the caseload wave is frustrating efforts to achieve testing aspirations. E.g., in Canada’s most populous province Ontario: “The number of people in hospital with COVID-19 has skyrocketed, and there has been an overall surge in infections, even as the government limited access to testing to groups deemed more at risk.” See Government of Canada and Toronto Star newspaper website, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111213040/https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2022/01/11/coronavirus-covid-19-updates-toronto-canada-january-11.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162230/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/symptoms/testing.html
column45: On 14 Jan. 2022, government of Canada advises that when individuals “test positive for COVID-19, a public health official will ask you questions to collect important information about your symptoms; activities and travel you did before you tested positive; all the people you may have been in close contact with while you were contagious ...contact tracing. It's a key public health measure.” Most provinces and territories intend to follow this practice, if conditions and resources permit. However, tracing capacity is not sufficient in many jurisdictions to deal with a surge in cases; e.g.: “volunteer with advocacy group Support Our Students Alberta, said she will continue tracking outbreaks in schools since the government has stopped contact tracing”; in the province of Saskatchewan: “the province’s chief medical health officer, said … the province’s health-care system can’t keep up with the rise in cases… public health follow up, case contact investigation, outbreak and contact investigation … just not possible anymore”; in Nova Scotia: “public health urging those who test positive to inform people with whom they’ve been in close contact. The province … is now limiting contact tracing to long-term care settings, health care facilities, correctional facilities, shelters and other group environments.”  See Government of Canada and Globe and Mail newspaper website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162230/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/symptoms/testing.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112204604/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-saskatchewan-schools-asked-to-take-on-contact-tracing-instead-of/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112132052/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/alberta/article-alberta-student-parents-say-they-feel-abandoned-as-k-12-kids-return-to/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112205754/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-atlantic-canada-hospitals-filling-with-covid-19-patients/
column52: On 14 jan. 2022, all provinces and territories continue to require masks in indoor public spaces consistent with Government of Canada advice: “a vaccines plus approach continues to be essential to the pandemic response in Canada. This includes … properly wearing a well-fitted and well-constructed face mask when in public or private spaces with others outside of your immediate household”. Even in the province of Saskatchewan, where there are no gathering limits, “ masks are mandatory in indoor public spaces”. See Government of Canada, Globe and Mail newspaper and McCarthly Law websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113154935/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2022/01/statement-from-the-chief-public-health-officer-of-canada-on-january-7-2022.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113154740/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-recovery-and-re-opening-tracker  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111210218/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/
column55: On 14 Jan. 2022, vaccinations are available to residents aged 5 and up. Provinces and territories are delivering third doses to long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, senior citizens and recipients of two earlier AZ doses based on national government guidance. The Government-of-Canada-recommended age for third doses has been lowered to those aged 50 and up and to age 18+ where local circumstances warrant. Some provinces have started delivering fourth doses. “Free vaccines will be available to everyone in Canada.” See government of Canada and CTV news websites, archived :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130147/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130237/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-booster-eligibility-by-province-and-territory-in-canada  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107190826/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/summary.pdf
column58: On 14 january 2022, provincial and territorial governments continue to be responsible for regulating long-term care (LTC) homes with the government of Canada providing guidance to protect residents and staff from covid-19. Some provinces and territories have restricted visitors. Most, but not all, provinces and territories restrict less-than-fully vaccinated persons from visiting LTC homes and some jurisdictions require LTC staff to be fully vaccinated or regularly show negative tests. E.g., in Ontario: “As of December 13, 2021, all staff had to be fully vaccinated to work in long-term care homes, unless they have a valid medical exemption. Visitors will also have to provide proof of all three doses in order to enter a long-term care home once the temporary pause on general visitors is lifted… the province announced it would be banning general visitors in long-term care and will be prohibiting residents from leaving on day absences for social purposes. Two designated caregivers per person may continue to enter the home.” See Yukon government as well as Globe and Mail and CTV news websites:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111210218/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113162155/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/long-term-care-visitation-guidelines-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107183346/https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-offering-fourth-covid-19-vaccine-dose-to-long-term-care-residents-mandating-booster-for-staff-1.5723637
column62: As of 14 january 2022, eligibility continues to be 5 years of age and up in all provinces and territories consistent with national government guidance. Provinces and territories have designated long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, those aged 50 and up, recipients of two earlier AZ doses as eligible for third doses based on national government guidance. In addition: “NACI [National Advisory Committee on Immunization] recommends that a [third] booster dose of an authorized mRNA COVID-19 vaccine may be offered =6 months after completion of a primary COVID-19 vaccine series to adults 18- 49 years of age with consideration of jurisdictional and individual risks…Adults who are moderately to severely immunocompromised who have received a three-dose primary series are included in those who may receive a booster dose. Data on a fourth dose of a COVID-19 vaccine after the recommended three-dose primary series in this population is currently limited. These individuals may receive a booster at least 6 months after receiving their last dose.” See government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107190826/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/summary.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130147/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130237/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-booster-eligibility-by-province-and-territory-in-canada
column64: On 14 Jan. 2022, availability is 5 years of age and up in all provinces and territories consistent with national government guidance. Vaccinations for those aged 5-11 have just started over the past several weeks. Based on national government guidance, provinces and territories are also delivering third doses to long-term care residents, immune-compromised patients, indigenous community residents, those aged 18 and up and recipients of two earlier AstraZeneca (AZ) doses. (AZ no longer used in Canada.) Some provinces have started delivering fourth doses. Data up to 1 jan. 2022 collected by the Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC) show 46% of Canadians aged 5-11 have received at least one dose, 87% of Canadians aged 12-39, rising steadily by age group to >95% aged 70+ with 2% of those aged 5-11 vaccinated having received at least two doses (or one Jannsen dose) , 83% of those aged 12-39, rising to 95% aged 70+. At least 17% of Canadians have received a booster dose on top of the initially required dose or doses (with data from Quebec and 2 Atlantic provinces not yet available). See government of Canada and CTV news websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107190826/https://www.canada.ca/content/dam/phac-aspc/documents/services/immunization/national-advisory-committee-on-immunization-naci/guidance-booster-covid-19-vaccine-doses/summary.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130147/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130237/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-booster-eligibility-by-province-and-territory-in-canada  https://web.archive.org/web/20220112133100/https://health-infobase.canada.ca/covid-19/vaccination-coverage/
column72: On 14 Jan. 2022: “Free vaccines will be available to everyone in Canada.” See government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113130147/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/coronavirus-disease-covid-19/vaccines.html

column29: On 15 January 2022, Canada remains open to entry by non-citizens, but only those who meet the following requirements: “you can enter Canada if you qualify as a fully vaccinated traveller or you’re coming for a non-optional purpose”. The government has effectively amended the definition of non-optional or essential worker to exclude less-than-fully-vaccinated truck drivers. “As of January 15, 2022, unvaccinated or partially vaccinated foreign national truck drivers, coming to Canada from the US by land, will be directed back to the United States…A Canadian truck driver who is not fully vaccinated can't be denied entry into Canada … starting January 15, unvaccinated Canadian truck drivers entering Canada will need to meet requirements for pre-entry, arrival and Day 8 testing, as well as quarantine requirements.” See Government of Canada website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113163702/https://travel.gc.ca/travel-covid/travel-restrictions/visitors-workers-students  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116121106/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2022/01/requirements-for-truckers-entering-canada-in-effect-as-of-january-15-2022.html

column12: On 17 January 2022, “non-essential businesses may open” in Nunavut Territory. Throughout Canada, businesses are open with different levels of restrictions in different provinces and territories. Many jurisdictions restrict access to some non-essential businesses to fully vaccinated customers (or require proof of a recent negative test). The Province of Alberta follows that approach, but allows an opt-out for businesses that do not wish to apply a vaccination/test mandate if they accept lower capacity limits. See Nunavut News and Globe and Mail newspaper and governments of Nunavut and Alberta websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120120728/https://www.gov.nu.ca/executive-and-intergovernmental-affairs/news/covid-19-gn-update-january-13-2022  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120121614/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-public-health-actions.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113210434/https://www.nunavutnews.com/news/nunavut-ending-lockdown-jan-17/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120121142/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/

column24: 18 Jan. 2022 is the first day after the end of the overnight curfew in the province of Quebec. “Curfew will end on January 17, 2022.” The Chief Public Health Officer of Canada recommends “staying home/self-isolating if you have symptoms”. Newfoundland and Labrador (NL) remains at Alert Level 4: “Stay at home as much as possible, except to get essentials like groceries and medications. Work from home, where possible.” See governments of Canada, Quebec and NL websites, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220116122109/https://www.quebec.ca/en/health/health-issues/a-z/2019-coronavirus/measures-in-force/curfew  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116122829/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2022/01/statement-from-the-chief-public-health-officer-of-canada-on-january-14-2022.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117121202/https://www.gov.nl.ca/covid-19/alert-levels/alert-level-4/

column12: Effective 19 Jan. 2022: “Quebec’s Nunavik region moved into lockdown … Nunavik Regional Board of Health and Social Services …, which spans the northern third of the province … all non-essential public places are closed.” In the rest of Canada, businesses are open with different levels of restrictions in different provinces and territories. Many jurisdictions restrict access to some non-essential businesses to fully vaccinated customers (or require proof of a recent negative test). See Globe and Mail newspaper website, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120121142/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-mandatory-vaccination-canada-province-territory-policies-guide/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220121135800/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-quebec-reports-88-more-covid-19-deaths-as-hospitalizations-rise-by/
column24: Effective 19 Jan. 2022 in “Quebec’s Nunavik region … 10 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew is in effect across the region, which spans the northern third of the province.”   The Chief Public Health Officer of Canada recommends “staying home/self-isolating if you have symptoms”. Newfoundland and Labrador (NL) remains at Alert Level 4: “Stay at home as much as possible, except to get essentials like groceries and medications. Work from home, where possible.” See Globe and Mail newspaper an governments of Canada and NL websites, archived:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220121135800/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-quebec-reports-88-more-covid-19-deaths-as-hospitalizations-rise-by/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116122829/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2022/01/statement-from-the-chief-public-health-officer-of-canada-on-january-14-2022.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117121202/https://www.gov.nl.ca/covid-19/alert-levels/alert-level-4/

column9: No evidence of policy change. Schools are open in Switzerland although they are subject to protective measures such as mask-wearing.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105154829/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column12: Working from home is mandatory in Switzerland. If that is not possible, masks must be worn in indoor spaces.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105154829/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column15: Access to indoor and outdoor events is limited to people holding a Covid certificate. There only exist limited exceptions, such as religious ceremonies or funerals.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105154829/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column18: No evidence of policy change. This is what can be read on the government's website:    "The number of people allowed to attend events among friends and family (for example gatherings and parties) that are not held in publicly accessible establishments and businesses is limited. The numbers include children.      Rule indoors without certificate: A maximum of 30 people is allowed.    If more than 10 people are present, it is recommended to limit access to people with a certificate.    Rule outdoors: A maximum of 50 people is allowed    Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105154829/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column21: No evidence of policy change.     link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105154829/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column29: There are several measures travelers must take in order to enter the country. Vaccinated or recovered individuals must complete an entry form and present a negative test.  Not recovered and not vaccinated individuals must fill out the entry form, present a negative test, and turn in a second negative test between 4-7 days upon the arrival.     The government of Switzerland had a ban in place for "countries with a variant of concern", which meant that travelers from these destinations were prohibited from entering the country. However, as of now, there are no countries under this category.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220105160134/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/empfehlungen-fuer-reisende/quarantaene-einreisende.html    http://web.archive.org/web/20220105160156/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/empfehlungen-fuer-reisende/liste.html

column9: No evidence of policy change. Schools remain mostly open in Switzerland under the application of certain protective measures such as mask-wearing. column12: Working at home is mandatory in Switzerland. If not possible, masks must be worn in indoor spaces. column15: Access to indoor and outdoor events is limited to people holding a Covid certificate. There only exist limited exceptions, such as religious ceremonies or funerals.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220115213925/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column18: No evidence of policy change. This is what can be read on the government's website:    "The number of people allowed to attend events among friends and family (for example gatherings and parties) that are not held in publicly accessible establishments is limited. The numbers include children.      Rule indoors without certificate: A maximum of 30 people is allowed if everyone is vaccinated or recovered. As soon as one person is present who is not vaccinated or recovered and is aged over 16, only up to 10 people may gather.    Rule outdoors: A maximum of 50 people is allowed."    Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220115213925/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column21: No policy change. Public transportation functions as normal in Switzerland.     Link:  https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/massnahmen-des-bundes.html
column29: There are several measures travelers must take in order to enter the country. Vaccinated or recovered individuals must complete an entry form and present a negative test.  Not recovered and not vaccinated individuals must fill out the entry form, present a negative test, and turn in a second negative test between 4-7 days upon the arrival.     The government of Switzerland had a ban in place for "countries with a variant of concern", which meant that travelers from these destinations were prohibited from entering the country. However, as of now, there are no countries under this category.     Link:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220115214529/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/empfehlungen-fuer-reisende/quarantaene-einreisende.html
column62: Although there are some groups that are highly encouraged to get the jab, there's no vaccine prioritization plan in Switzerland. At this point, the inoculation campaign has become universal. Anyone above 5 years old can receive the vaccine. column27: On 1 November, the Plan "Paso a Paso" was refreshed. column29: On 30 December, 2021 ,the Plan "Fronteras protegidas" was refreshed. On the other hand, flexibilities continue for foreign travellers who travelled by airplane and they present a negative PCR test in the Chile airport. column15: Anhui Government recommended to during the festival period, the general public is requested not to organize or participate in non-essential gathering activities, reduce the flow of people, advocate the citizens to "delay red matters as much as possible, handle white matters briefly, and do not hold banquets", and advocate family dinner gatherings with no more than 10 people.  Anhui Government recommended to all kinds of large-scale conferences and offline trainings should not be held unless it is necessary, and all kinds of conferences and trainings should be held online; party and government organs at all levels, enterprises and institutions are not allowed to hold large-scale gatherings of people conferences and activities without approval. Cancellation of group worship, large-scale condolences, gatherings, dinners, annual meetings and other activities that must be held, according to the principle of "who hosts, who is responsible", implement the main responsibility for prevention and control, and strictly control the number, scale and time.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220123143718/http://www.aaas.org.cn/wap/content/article/19710951

column9: No policy change was found. The newest policy of Shandong are as follows:  Persons entering or returning from locally affected areas should hold negative nucleic acid test proof within 48 hours and take nucleic acid test again upon arrival at destination.  Persons entering or returning to Shandong from counties (cities, districts and banners) in medium-high risk areas shall be quarantined for 7 days and monitored at home for 7 days upon arrival.  Persons from other counties (cities, districts or banners) in prefecture-level cities with medium-high risk areas entering (returning) Shandong shall hold negative nucleic acid test proof within 48 hours and undergo nucleic acid test once upon arrival.  Persons returning to Or entering Shandong with a history of living in a land border port city within the last 14 days shall take a nucleic acid test upon arrival upon proof of negative nucleic acid test within 48 hours.  URL: http://archive.today/Xg4pb

column27: From January 2, Ningbo railway station will resume the implementation of the strict control of cross provincial travel policy according to the provincial epidemic prevention and control requirements: the travel of personnel in Beilun District of Ningbo will be strictly restricted; Personnel from other districts and counties (cities) in Ningbo do not travel unnecessarily. column18: The leading group of epidemic prevention and control of infectious diseases in Ningbo, New Coronavirus, was released in January 15th. According to the principle of "no need not to hold", strict control of Temple Fair (folk activities), large-scale theatrical performances, large-scale forums, sales promotion and other activities. Religious (folk belief) activity sites shall be opened in an orderly manner. All participants shall not exceed 60% of the accommodation scale of the site. column24: Yuhang District of Hangzhou issued on January 15 that the sealed control area strictly implements the management measures of "closed isolation, staying at home and providing door-to-door service", and arranges staff for 24-hour patrol and door-to-door service. In the control area, personnel can only enter and leave, and personnel gathering is strictly prohibited. In principle, they are isolated at home. The prevention area is not necessary to leave Yuhang District. If it is really necessary to go in and out for medical treatment or specific official business, it must hold the negative certificate of nucleic acid test within 48 hours. Pupils from 1st grade onwards and staff in primary and lower secondary school are strongly encouraged to get tested on a weekly basis, unless they are fully vaccinated or previously infected with COVID-19 within the last 6 months. Two weekly tests are recommended in municipalities and parishes with high infection rates.      Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220106183339/https://en.coronasmitte.dk/rules-and-regulations

column29: For people entering Denmark from an EU and / or Schengen country or COVID-19 risk country, there is no requirement for isolation after entry.    However, those entering from a COVID-19 high-risk country must self-isolate after entry, unless they are fully vaccinated or previously infected. The isolation is required for 10 days but the isolation may be ended after a negative PCR test taken at the earliest on the sixth day after the time of entry.
