In additon, the government announced SGD$130 million (Approx USD$ 95 million) stimuli in the form of cash vouchers that can be utilized at select merchants across the country,    ___________________  Quote (1):  "SINGAPORE - All Singaporean households can now collect $100 worth of vouchers that they can spend at about 10,000 participating hawkers and heartland merchants.    The community development council (CDC) vouchers, worth $130 million in total and given out to 1.3 million households, are available for collection digitally from Monday (Dec 13) and can be used till Dec 31, 2022."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211213094222/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/100-worth-of-cdc-vouchers-for-each-sporean-household-available-for-collection-online  ________________    Quote (2): [Exchange Rate]  "Dec 13, 2021 09:38 UTC  Singapore Dollar	130,000,000.00 SGD	  US Dollar	95035922.924214	@ 1.367904"    Link (2): https://web.archive.org/web/20211213094242/https://www.x-rates.com/historical/?from=SGD&amount=130000000&date=2021-12-13  ______________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 19 Nov 2021:    No coding changes for the period of 07-19 Nov 2021.     ____________________________________  ****Please refer to previous notes dated 6 Nov 2021:    no coding changes to the period of 02-06 Nov 2021.   ___________________  ***Please refer to notes dates 01 Nov 2021:    No coding changes for the period of 24 Oct -01 Nov.  ___________________  *** Please refer to notes dates 23 Oct 2021    Support to continue until Nov 21 in light of the further extensions of the current restrictions.  ___________________    Quote (1):  "SINGAPORE: A S$640 million support package will be rolled out for affected businesses and workers, after it was announced on Wednesday (Oct 20) that Singapore will extend its COVID-19 restrictions by nearly a month.  The stabilisation phase, which started on Sep 27 to help reduce the strain on the healthcare system, was scheduled to last until Oct 24.   It has now been extended until Nov 21, with a review of the measures at the two-week mark. They may be adjusted based on the situation then, said the Ministry of Health (MOH) in a media release.  During the stabilisation phase, social gatherings and dining-in have been capped at groups of two, while work-from-home has been the default arrangement.  Given the extended restrictions, the Government will continue with the Jobs Support Scheme until Nov 21, at 25 per cent wage support for sectors significantly affected by the tightened measures.  These include F&B, retail, cinemas, museums and art galleries, family entertainment, tourism, gyms and fitness studios, as well as performing arts and arts education.  A two-week rental waiver will be given to qualifying tenants on government-owned commercial properties.  Eligible tenant-occupiers and owner-occupiers of privately-owned commercial properties will also be given a 0.5-month rental relief cash payout under the Rental Support Scheme (RSS).  Cooked food and market stallholders in centres managed by the National Environment Agency (NEA) or operators appointed by NEA will receive a 0.5-month rental waiver.    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20211023041636/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/singapore/covid-19-support-package-jobs-support-scheme-extended-restrictions-2257036

Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20220106084209/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/current-covid-19-rules-will-stay-during-cny-period-in-view-of-omicron-wave-lawrence-wong.    ______________________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 18 Dec 2021:  No coding changes for the period of 14-18 Dec 2021. _  __________   ***Please refer to notes dated 13 Dec 2021:  Face masks continue to be mandated any time outside of the home. _    ______________    Quote (1): ""How does COVID-19 spread? Current evidence suggests that transmission of COVID-19 occurs primarily through the respiratory droplets of infected people, which are expelled when an infected person coughs, sneezes, talks or sings. These respiratory droplets can reach the eyes, nose or mouth of a susceptible person directly or indirectly (via contaminated surfaces), resulting in infection.  Airborne transmission of the virus can occur in health care settings where aerosol-generating procedures are performed. While there have been limited reports of airborne transmission outside of health care settings internationally, its role and extent are under further study. MOH will continue to monitor the evidence as it emerges.  To reduce the risk of spread, members of public must wear a mask outside the home and observe safe distancing. Individuals should also observe good hand hygiene and avoid crowded spaces if possible.""      Link (1): https://web.archive.org/web/20211206075819/https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19/general

column58: No coding changes for the period of 07-17 January 2022.  All restrictions will remain the same all the way to and during the Chinese New Year (CNY) period in Early to mid February 2022.    Link [1]: http://archive.today/2022.01.17-030005/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/current-covid-19-rules-will-stay-during-cny-period-in-view-of-omicron-wave-lawrence-wong  Link [2]: http://archive.today/2022.01.17-030048/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/no-plans-relax-covid-19-curbs-chinese-new-year-holidays-lawrence-wong-1784181  Link [3]: http://archive.today/2022.01.17-030109/https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/government-economy/we-dont-intend-to-relax-further-says-lawrence-wong-as-covid-curbs-look-set-to  Link [4]: http://archive.today/2022.01.17-030130/https://www.gov.sg/article/safe-management-measures-and-chinese-new-year  ____________________  *** Please refer to previous notes:    No Coding Changes to the period of 01-06 January 2022. Recent updates from the government states that in light of the Omicron variant, the current Covid-19 safety measurements will remain unchanged right into the Chinese New Year (CNY) period - this commences on the 01-02 February 2022 and normally the period stretches for 14 days.  ________________________    Quote (1):  "SINGAPORE - Singapore's current set of Covid-19 safe management rules will stay in place during the upcoming Chinese New Year period from Feb 1, in view of a likely surge of infections brought about by the new Omicron variant, said Finance Minister Lawrence Wong on Wednesday (Jan 5). Group sizes for gathering and dining at restaurants have been capped at five since November, when Singapore emerged from an outbreak caused by the earlier Delta variant. Mr Wong, who is a co-chair of the multi-ministry task force handling Covid-19, said during a press conference that the present posture would be maintained as he could not imagine the Omicron wave passing before Chinese New Year."    Link (1): http://web.archive.org/web/20220106084209/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/current-covid-19-rules-will-stay-during-cny-period-in-view-of-omicron-wave-lawrence-wong.    ______________________    ***Please also refer to notes dated 18 Dec 2021:    "No coding changes for the period of 14-18 Dec 2021.   ___________   ***Please refer to notes dated 13 Dec 2021:  No coding changes to the period of 03-13 Dec 2021.   ______________________________________   *** Please refer to notes dated 02 Dec 2021:    No coding changes to the period of 22Nov - 02 Dec 2021. Resumption of in-person visits have commenced, however, each institution have implemented tight restrictions with regards to how in-person visits will take place. An example of a Nursing in Singapore is below.    _____________   Quote (1):   "RESUMPTION of face-to-face visits in OVNH, for both FULLY VACCINATED (“FV”) residents and visitors. Only 1 designated fully vaccinated visitor allowed per visit per day for each fully vaccinated resident, for a maximum of 30 mins each time.  Visitation hours are from 10am - 2pm and 4pm - 8pm daily.  Video calls and telephone calls remain for Unvaccinated residents. Please call our branches to pre-register. Thank you for your support as we do our utmost best during this period.  • Balestier: (65) 6250 6636 • Changi : (65) 6545 5977 • Clementi: (65) 6873 9988 • Marsiling : (65) 6362 7333 • Simei: (65) 6260 0020  Please note: ? Each FV resident will be allowed 3 designated FV visitors, maximum of 1 visitation per week. ? Only 1 designated FV visitor per FV resident will be allowed per visit per day for a maximum of 30 mins each time. ? The same designated FV visitor must have an interval of 10 days before their next visitation. ? Non-designated FV visitors will not be allowed to enter the premises. ? No outside food is allowed."    Link (1): http://archive.today/2021.12.02-033425/https://www.facebook.com/OVNHSG/

column24: You are sick.  You tested positive for COVID-19 and haven’t ended isolation.  After you end isolation, avoid travel until a full 10 days after your symptoms started or the date of your positive test if you had no symptoms.  You had close contact with a person with COVID-19 and haven’t ended quarantine.  Get tested at least 5 days after your last close contact and make sure your test result is negative and you remain without symptoms before traveling. you must travel before the 10 days are completed, properly wear a well-fitting mask when you are around others for the entire duration of travel during the 10 days. If you are unable to wear a mask, you should not travel during the 10 days.  You are waiting for the results of a COVID-19 test. If your test comes back positive while you are at your destination, you will need to isolate and postpone your return until it’s safe for you to end isolation. Your travel companions may need to quarantine.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106053809/https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/covid-4/coronavirus-south-sudan

column29: Fully vaccinated persons travelling from high-risk countries do not need permission.    The following documents are required prior to boarding an airplane:    Proof of complete vaccination with a WHO EUL COVID-19 vaccine, or a COVID-19 recovery certificate not older than six months.  Negative SARS-CoV-2 PCR test result not older than 48 hours issued by an accredited medical test entity before departure.  Valid travel documents.  Medical insurance/ COVID-19 insurance (with at least 30-day coverage)  Yellow fever certificate for persons traveling from or transiting countries with risk of yellow fever transmission.  After arrival in Suriname passengers will have to observe the following:    A SARS-CoV-2 antigen test must be taken 3 days after arrival in Suriname at one of the following test locations:  · The Bureau of Public Health Suriname (BOG)  · MeDiLab  · Mylab  · The Academic Hospital (AZ)  · Health Control.    b) Fully vaccinated persons travelling from low or medium-risk countries do not need permission. The following documents are required:    Proof of complete vaccination with a WHO EUL COVID-19 vaccine or a COVID-19 recovery certificate not older than six months.  Negative SARS-CoV-2 PCR test result issued by an accredited medical test entity not older than 72 hours before departure or a negative SAR-CoV-2 antigen test result within 24 hours before departure.  Valid travel documents.  Medical insurance/ COVID-19 insurance (with at least 30-day coverage)  Yellow fever certificate for persons traveling from or transiting countries with risk of yellow fever transmission.  For above passengers traveling to Suriname, it is advised to observe a seven day self- or home-quarantine after arrival.  Exception will be made for Surinamese residents who are not or not-fully vaccinated against COVID-19 to travel to Suriname.    The following categories of persons can apply for an entry permit at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, International Business and International Cooperation; conza@gov.sr    i. Surinamese Residents (Repatriants)  ii. Diplomats  iii. Persons who in connection with the death of a relative or visit of a seriously ill relative (only first-degree relatives)  The following conditions will apply:    Immediately after arrival in Suriname a 7-day compulsory hotel quarantine with surveillance must be observed.  Presentation of a negative SARS-CoV-2 PCR test result not older than 48 hours before departure.  A SARS-CoV-2 antigen test must be taken 3 days after arrival in Suriname.  Valid travel documents.  For the repatriants a proof of permanent residency in Suriname must be provided when applying for an entry permit.  For category iii:  Medical insurance/COVID-19 insurance (with at least 30 days coverage).  Yellow fever certificate for persons traveling from or transiting countries with risk of yellow fever transmission.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220122150928/https://sr.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/

column12: Employees are only able to enter workplaces if they are either fully vaccinated, contracted COVID-19 in the last 180 days, proof of a negative COVID-19 test or has a proof of vaccine exemption. column15: Mass events can now go ahead under strict restrictions. Events have been categorised into low, medium and high risk:  - Low risk: capacity of 100 or 50% of venue maximum capacity. Defined as events where participants are wearing masks, food and drinks are prohibited, sitting is mandatory, and event takes place without singing, encouragement or other loud vocal expressions.  - Medium risk: capacity of 100 or 25% of venue maximum capacity. Defined as events where participants are wearing masks and here is a fixed sitting or standing arrangement.   - High risk: capacity of 20 people. Defined as events in a public catering operation or a non-low-risk mass event and a medium-risk mass event; this includes weddings, parties and other celebrations.   All mass event attendees must be fully vaccinated or have proof of full COVID-19 recovery within the past 90 days. Funerals are exempt from these restrictions, as are meetings of public authorities, elections, and mass events necessary for the course of the following professional competitions in selected sports.  Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20220123200410/https://korona.gov.sk/obmedzenia-pre-hromadne-podujatia/ & http://web.archive.org/web/20220123195717/https://www.uvzsr.sk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4988%3Ainformacia-k-novym-vyhlakam-uvz-sr-respiratory-hromadne-podujatia-prevadzky-otp-na-pracoviskach&catid=56%3Atlaove-spravy&Itemid=62

column12: The Thai government has ordered entertainment venues catering to the nightlife to remain closed for the foreseeable future. While the government intends to relax restrictions in other economic sectors, it views these venues as being particularly high-risk for COVID-19 transmission.     Correlates with Tourism Authority of Thailand update on 23rd January 2022, stating that “all types of entertainment venues, including pubs, bars, and karaoke shops nationwide are to remain closed until further notice.”     It is noted that in practice, some of such venues have been able to re-open as “restaurants” or “eateries” if they alter their services and meet certain government requirements. Other sources state that some entertainment venues that have not properly converted to restaurants have also re-opened illegally. Nonetheless coded as 2G to reflect official government policy, and because in practice, venues that do not have kitchen facilities are unable to legally convert to a restaurant.     1.	Tourism Authority of Thailand update: https://archive.vn/ft5i4  2. column15: 18th January 2022: Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA) announces that it will cancel the Chinese New Year celebrations that it normally organises at Bangkok's Yaowarat Road/Chinatown, due to concerns over Omicron variant. However, apart from this specific government-organised event in Bangkok, have not found evidence of the BMA or other Thai authorities requiring other public events held by private actors to be cancelled.   The government offered safety tips for Chinese New Year, but there is no mention of ban on public events, it is phrased as “advice” for people to generally avoid crowded places. Therefore, coded as 1G because there is a recommendation to avoid crowds, but without an actual requirement to cancel events.   Archived sources:  1. Thai Government Public Relations Department (official Facebook page) (English): https://archive.ph/OeRkH 2. Matichon Online Newspaper (Thai): https://archive.ph/aO9zp 3. The Nation | Thailand (English): "No Chinese New Year celebrations in Chinatown.": https://archive.ph/0a6Np  4. column18: Thailand utilises a colour-coded zoning system for COVID-19 restrictions (From high restrictions to low: Red, Orange, Yellow, Blue). Presently, no provinces are classified red or yellow, but most provinces (69 out of 76) are in the orange zone for the period of 18th—23rd January 2022. In orange zones, gatherings of no more than 500 people are permitted. Government announced on 20th January that it will relax restrictions and move 25 provinces from orange to yellow zone, but this will only take effect on 24th January 2022.     Coded 2G because although some provinces are in the more relaxed blue zone (where restrictions have been eased with an eye on allowing tourism to recover), the vast majority of provinces (69/76) have orange zone restrictions.     Archived sources:  1. Tourism Authority Thailand update stating that 69 provinces will be designated in the orange zone with effect from 9th January 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220122213830/https://www.tatnews.org/2022/01/thailand-steps-up-covid-19-curbs-nationwide-from-9-january-2022/  2. Bangkok Post article dated 21st January 2022, confirming that 69 provinces are presently in the orange zone: https://archive.vn/GIewc
column29: Differentiated rules based on vaccination status, with stricter rules for unvaccinated travellers to Thailand (the "Alternative Quarantine" scheme). Unvaccinated travellers to Thailand must quarantine for 10 days and undergo 2 PCR tests upon arrival. Before arriving in Thailand, a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours of departure is also required, except for travellers under the age of 6. Travellers from any country in the world can enter via this scheme.     Additional notes: Vaccinated travellers can undergo a shorter 7-day quarantine, but must also take pre-departure and upon-arrival PCR tests. The Thai government announced on that it will further relax international travel controls, but these will come into effect only on 1st February 2022.     Archived sources:  1. Royal Thai Embassy, Canberra: “Schemes for entering Thailand” (English): https://archive.vn/nlmpY  5.	Tourism Authority of Thailand (English): https://archive.vn/i8WT6
column41: Coordinated and detailed public information campaign on the Thai government's official websites, as well as accounts on social media platforms (Facebook, Twitter). Information campaign is in both Thai and English, on a variety of issues: providing nationwide COVID-19 statistics daily, advice about taking precautions when working-from-home, caring for vulnerable/elderly individuals and vaccination information. Many pages include links to regular press conferences given by Thai officials. As of this date, the pages have been updated regularly, often multiple times a day.     Archived sources:  1. column29: Timor-Leste Travel update from UK government website:  -A State of Emergency is no longer in place in Timor-Leste. The latest one ended on 28 November 2021. Entry to national territory is no longer subject to authorisation from the Prime Minister, while entry to the country continues to be subject to medical screening. If a passenger is found infected with COVID-19, he or she will be taken to quarantine for further consultation and treatment. All passengers travelling to Timor-Leste should always present to the airport competent authorities the following: vaccination certificate and a negative COVID-19 PCR test result done within the last 72 hours before the time of departure. The test needs to be in one of these language: Indonesian, Portuguese or English. Failure to present the two documents, will be subjected to 14 days of quarantine.  -It is mandatory for all individuals to practice COVID-19 safety measures, including wearing a mask, washing hands frequently, and maintaining social distance of at least two metres.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221559/https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/timor-leste/coronavirus

column32: Key Policy Responses as of July 1, 2021    FISCAL  The revised 2021 budget approved in late April includes an unprecedented fiscal response to deal with the recent COVID-19 outbreak. The COVID-19 Fund was increased to 17.7 percent of non-oil GDP. The funds will be used to purchase vaccines, protective equipment, and more material for testing and treatment. They will also finance employment support, internet connection for students, a supplement for front-line workers, and a basic consumption basket.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220117233826/https://www.imf.org/en/Topics/imf-and-covid19/Policy-Responses-to-COVID-19#T
column34: Key Policy Responses as of July 1, 2021    MONETARY AND MACRO-FINANCIAL  The authorities introduced a credit moratorium for 3 months in August 2020 which led to 23 percent of total bank loans being restructured. This scheme has been reintroduced for 2021, with an extended duration of 9 months. Moreover, the credit guarantee scheme was extended to cover micro-enterprises in addition to small and medium enterprises.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220117233826/https://www.imf.org/en/Topics/imf-and-covid19/Policy-Responses-to-COVID-19#T

column29: All incoming travelers who are unvaccinated are required to complete a 10-day quarantine upon arrival. Unvaccinated travelers must present a paid voucher for a government-sanctioned hotel, as well as a self-funded PCR test done the last day of quarantine. In the case of a positive PCR test following the quarantine period, the traveler will be transported to a COVID isolation center to be treated at their own expense.  Children under the age of 18 who are unaccompanied or who are travelling with vaccinated adults are exempt from mandatory quarantine.   Fully vaccinated travelers are exempt from the mandatory quarantine requirement upon presentation of their official vaccination card.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116073448/https://tn.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/

Yes  If so, are test results reliably available within one calendar day? Yes. column27: As of 6th  September 2021, intercity travel by bus, plane, train or other public transportation requires proof of vaccination or a negative PCR test taken within the past 48 hours. column29: A PCR test is required for individuals over the age of 12 years old who are unable to show proof of vaccination.  Passengers arriving in Turkey will be required to complete an information form and will be checked for symptoms. Passengers may be subject to a PCR test by means of the method of sampling at points of arrival in Turkey. If their test results are positive, they shall be taken under treatment in accordance with the COVID-19 Guidelines of the Ministry of Health. The passengers with positive test results and persons having been in close contact with such passengers shall be taken under quarantine for a period of 7 days at the addresses they have determined, and if the results of the PCR tests to be taken at the end of the 5th day are negative, the quarantine shall be ended. The quarantines of these people who are identified to have Delta variant shall be ended upon submitting a negative PCR test result at the end of the 7th day.    Passengers must have a negative COVID-19 PCR test taken at most 72 hours before arrival, if arriving from or they have been in Afghanistan, South Africa, Botswana, Mozambique, Namibia, Zimbabwe, Brazil, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, India and Pakistan in the last 14 days (This does not apply to passengers under 12). Passengers arriving from Egypt and Iran must have a negative COVID-19 PCR test taken at most 72 hours before arrival (This does not apply to passengers under 12). Effective 10th January 2022, passengers arriving from a country other than above countries do not need to submit negative PCR /rapid antigen test if they fit into one of the following categories; passengers younger than 12 years; passengers with a COVID-19 vaccination certificate showing that they were fully vaccinated at least 14 days before arrival; passengers with a COVID-19 recovery certificate issued at most 6 months before arrival; merchant seamen.  http://web.archive.org/web/20220123182623/https://tr.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information-2/

column9: Several school districts across the country are remaining closed to in-person learning following the holiday break.     See Pennsylvania:   Latest bulletin:   As we begin the new year, school leaders are requesting updated COVID-19 guidance, particularly to changes that have occurred to the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) close contact and quarantine practices.    At this time, schools should follow the most recent PA Department of Health (DOH) Health Alert (PA-HAN) on Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population that was released last Thursday. (615 - 12/30/2021 - UPD - UPDATE: Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population (PDF))    As with previous updates in guidance, schools are expected to follow the new community guidelines. The CDC has indicated that there will be additional guidance for more specific settings, including schools, released in the near future. DOH will review and update the community guidance in the PA-HAN accordingly if and when CDC makes any further adjustments. Please note that this is a very fluid situation. We appreciate your patience as we work through these changes together.    https://archive.vn/pEyJ8    Two southeastern Pennsylvania school districts announces school closures due to the coronavirus on the heels of their winter breaks. column43: Testing is generally available across the US.     See North Carolina:   Fully vaccinated individuals should get tested if they:  -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.  -Have had close contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. You should get tested within 3-5 days after exposure.  -Are traveling internationally and returning to the United States. Fully vaccinated international travelers are required to get tested three days before travel by air into the U.S. and should also get tested 3-5 days after their trip.    Unvaccinated individuals should get tested if they:   -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.   -Have come in contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. If they do not have symptoms, they should wait at least six days after their last known exposure to COVID-19 before they get tested.  -Take part in activities that put them at higher risk for COVID-19 because they cannot physically distance as needed to avoid exposure, such as travel, attending large social or mass gatherings, or being in crowded or poorly ventilated indoor settings.    If available through an employer or another organization, unvaccinated individuals can be part of a program where they get tested regularly for COVID-19.    See Archive:  https://archive.vn/fUjTw

column27: DC is currently enforcing different guidelines for domestic travelers based on vaccination status. Unvaccinated Visitors        Unvaccinated or partially vaccinated travelers must follow COVID-19 testing and quarantining requirements for non-essential travel. Proof of vaccination is generally required to visit indoor gathering locations. If visitors are requesting medical or religious exemption, documentation and proof of a negative antigen or PCR test within 24 hours is required. General travel requirements for unvaccinated visitors include getting a COVID-19 test 1-3 days before visiting DC, getting a COVID-19 test 3-5 days after returning home from their trip and self-quarantining for 7 days after returning home. You do not need a COVID-19 test if traveling from Maryland and Virginia or in DC in less than 24 hours. Private institutions and local government officials may ask for proof of a negative test.            If a traveler tests positive while in DC, they must complete their isolation before traveling home, and susceptible close contacts must complete a 10-day quarantine." column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111065215/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html
column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals.    The July 29th order from Biden still stands, ordering federal workers to be vaccinated or subject themselves to constant masking and frequent testing.     Given that the public transit policy affects more people and is stricter, this is now coded as a 2G - Universal.     See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101145401/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/masks.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fprevent-getting-sick%2Fdiy-cloth-face-coverings.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111194558/https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/masks/mask-travel-guidance.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111035057/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/face-masks-public-transportation.html

column43: Free tests are widely available at doctor’s offices, pharmacies, and numerous other locations around the state. Doctor's approval is not needed to get tested.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105211152/https://benefitoptions.az.gov/covidtesting
column45: The Arizona Department of Health is conducting a program for contact tracing. Those who might have been in contact with someone who has tested positive for Covid will be notified via email or text message.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220103233023/https://www.azdhs.gov/covid19/index.php
column52: "Pima County leaders reinstated a countywide indoor mask mandate Tuesday as COVID-19 rates persist at high levels and in anticipation of a spike from the more contagious omicron variant. The governor has already reiterated that Arizona doesn’t allow mask mandates and that businesses by law don’t have to enforce them. The Pima County Board of Supervisors voted 3-2 to require people to wear masks indoors in public when they can’t distance by six feet. However, the county hasn't specified plans to enforce it and views it as more of an educational tool."  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105212615/https://webcms.pima.gov/cms/One.aspx?portalId=169&pageId=563362

column58: "Visitors who are unvaccinated or incompletely vaccinated must show documentation of a negative SARS-CoV-2 test that occurred within 72 hours before each indoor visit."   "Any visitor entering the facility, regardless of their vaccination status, must adhere to the following:    "All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must be screened for fever and COVID-19 symptoms and/or exposure within the prior 14 days to another person with COVID-19; if a visitor has COVID-19 symptoms or has been in close contact with a confirmed positive case, they must reschedule their visit, regardless of their vaccination status.  All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must wear a well-fitting face mask (medical masks, also called surgical masks, or double masking is recommended) and perform hand hygiene upon entry and in all common areas in the facility;   If personal protective equipment (PPE) is required for contact with the resident due to quarantine or COVID-19 positive isolation status (including fully vaccinated visitors), it must be donned and doffed according to instruction by HCP.  All visitors, regardless of their vaccination status, must follow physical distancing guidelines and maintain at least 6 feet distance from other visitors from different households, as well as from facility staff and other residents;   Facilities should limit visitor movement in the facility, regardless of the visitor's vaccination status; for example, visitors should not walk around the hallways of the facility and should go directly to and from the resident's room or designated visitation area."    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220110221827/https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHCQ/LCP/Pages/AFL-20-22.aspx

column12: According to a published report by CDC workplaces are obliged to:  "Develop an Infectious Disease Preparedness  and Response Plan  If one does not already exist, develop an infectious disease  preparedness and response plan that can help guide protective  actions against COVID-19.  Stay abreast of guidance from federal, state, local, tribal, and/or  territorial health agencies, and consider how to incorporate those  recommendations and resources into workplace-specific plans.  Plans should consider and address the level(s) of risk  associated with various worksites and job tasks workers  perform at those sites. Such considerations may include:  ¦ Where, how, and to what sources of SARS-CoV-2 might  workers be exposed, including:  { The general public, customers, and coworkers; and  { Sick individuals or those at particularly high risk  of infection (e.g., international travelers who have  visited locations with widespread sustained (ongoing)  COVID-19 transmission, healthcare workers who have  had unprotected exposures to people known to have, or  suspected of having, COVID-19).  ¦ Non-occupational risk factors at home and in community  settings.    Coded 0 since work places are not closing down.    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.osha.gov/sites/default/files/publications/OSHA3990.pdf

column27: Fully vaccinated visitors (or visitors who tested positive for COVID-19 in the previous 90 days) may travel to DC from domestic locations without quarantining unless showing symptoms of COVID-19. Fully vaccinated is defined as 14 days after the second dose of a 2-dose series, or after one dose of a single-dose vaccine.     Unvaccinated visitors don't need a COVID-19 test if travelling from Maryland and Virginia or if they are in DC less than 24 hours. For non-essential travel, people must get a COVID-19 test 1-3 days before visiting DC. If a traveler tests positive while in DC, they must complete their isolation before traveling home, and susceptible close contacts must complete a 10-day quarantine.  Moreover, a test is required if essential travelers have more than 1 week of notice.     See Archive:  https://archive.vn/KOFps

column27: According to DC's travel status:  "Fully Vaccinated Visitors (or visitors who tested positive for COVID-19 in the previous 90 days) may:         Travel to DC from domestic locations without quarantining unless showing symptoms of COVID-19.   Unvaccinated Visitors        Unvaccinated or partially vaccinated travelers must follow COVID-19 testing and quarantining requirements for non-essential travel. Proof of vaccination is generally required to visit indoor gathering locations. If visitors are requesting medical or religious exemption, documentation and proof of a negative antigen or PCR test within 24 hours is required. General travel requirements for unvaccinated visitors include getting a COVID-19 test 1-3 days before visiting DC, getting a COVID-19 test 3-5 days after returning home from their trip and self-quarantining for 7 days after returning home. You do not need a COVID-19 test if traveling from Maryland and Virginia or in DC in less than 24 hours. Private institutions and local government officials may ask for proof of a negative test.            If a traveler tests positive while in DC, they must complete their isolation before traveling home, and susceptible close contacts must complete a 10-day quarantine."    Coded 1 since travellers have to follow the set Covid 19 guideliness.    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://washington.org/dc-information/coronavirus-travel-update-washington-dc

COVID-19 Guidance for Georgia Child Care Facilities remains in place and the state's Department of Public Health webpage refers to CDC's guideline for schools and higher institution.  Students benefit from in-person learning, and safely returning to in-person instruction continues to be a priority. In addition to universal indoor masking, CDC recommends schools maintain at least 3 feet of physical distance between students within classrooms to reduce transmission risk. column9: The Hawai‘i Department of Health (DOH) has updated interim COVID-19 isolation and quarantine guidance for K-12 schools. The updated guidance is closely aligned with new CDC guidance for schools.   1. Students and staff who test positive for COVID-19 or have COVID-19 symptoms should isolate for five days regardless of their vaccination status. They can return to school when all the following conditions are met:    - Five full days have passed since symptoms first appeared or since test was conducted.    - No fever for 24 hours.    - Symptoms have improved.  2. Students and staff who have been in close contact with a person who has COVID-19 should quarantine for five days after last contact if:    - They have not completed their primary vaccine series (2 shots Pfizer or Moderna, 1 shot J&J).    - They are 18 or older and have completed their primary vaccine series but have not received a recommended booster when eligible.  Students and staff should get tested on day five of quarantine, even if they do not have symptoms.  3. Students and staff are not required to quarantine if:    - They are ages 5-17 and have completed their primary series of COVID-19 vaccines (2 shots Pfizer or Moderna).    - They are 18 and older and have received all recommended vaccine doses including boosters.    In addition, everyone, regardless of vaccination status, is required to wear well-fitting masks in all indoor settings and in outdoor settings where crowding may occur. Masks may be removed when actively eating and drinking and during nap time for young children.    Moreover, the updated Guidance for Schools continues to provide multiple mitigation strategies to help solw the spread of the SARS-CoV-2 and maintain safe school environments and operations.    See Archive:  - https://archive.vn/vJaP6  - https://archive.vn/gPbB2  - https://archive.vn/iUvDq

column27: For travelers from the U.S and it territories, the State of Hawai'i Safe Travels program includes temperature screening at all Hawai'i airports upon arrival, and the mandatory five-day quarantine with the possibility of a vaccination exception or a negative pre-travel test to bypass quarantine. Individuals arriving from the U.S or its territories who are up to date on their vaccination may enter Hawai'i without pre-travel testing/quarantine starting the 14th day after the completion of their vaccination. The vaccination record document must be uploaded onto Safe Travels and printed out prior to departure and the traveler must have a hard copy in hand when arriving in Hawai'i. The State of Hawai'i will also accept vaccine records that are digitally validated by Digital Health Pass Partners.    In addition, the pre-travel testing program remains available for all travelers from the U.S. or its territories who are not vaccinated.    See Archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115020603/https://hawaiicovid19.com/travel/travel-overview/

column34: The Emergency Rental Assistance (ERA) program assists households that are unable to pay rent and/or utilities due to the COVID-19 pandemic.     Eligible renter households are those with incomes of no more than 80% of area median income (AMI) who also meet the following conditions:  - Priority is given to households with incomes of no more than 50% of AMI as well as to households in which one or more household members were unemployed for 90 days prior to application.  - One or more individuals in the household has qualified for unemployment benefits or experienced a reduction in household income, incurred significant costs, or experienced other financial hardship due, directly or indirectly, to the coronavirus outbreak; and  - One or more individuals in the household can demonstrate a risk of experiencing homelessness or housing instability. This may include a past due rental or utility notice, an eviction notice unsafe or unhealthy living conditions (such as overcrowding) or any other evidence of risk.    See Archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117195443/https://dbedt.hawaii.gov/hhfdc/assistance-for-renters-emergency-rental-assistance-era-program/

column45: As of 17 January 2022,    "Leaders with the Iowa Department of Public Health have changed the way they approach COVID-19 to investigate positive cases and contact trace possible exposures, according to a new state document. column27: Update January 4, 2022 (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Recommends that both vaccinated and unvaccinated wear masks throughout travel:    "Delay travel until you are fully vaccinated. Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. CDC recommends you get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose if you are eligible. People who are not fully vaccinated should follow additional recommendations before, during, and after travel."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220117005204/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html
column29: On January 4th, 2022, this was updated with no change in policy stringency. The present policy continues to have rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220117161912/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html
column43: Testing is still generally available. The CDC recommends that anyone symptomatic or those at risk (unvaccinated or had close contact with an infected person get tested).     See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220115060812/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/symptoms-testing/testing.html
column45: Contact tracing is primarily conducted at the state level, but the CDC is serving in both a guiding and supportive role with contact tracing. It varies, some states are sufficiently conducting contact tracing and others are doing so on a limited basis.     Updated Jan 11, 2022:   "CDC has updated isolation and quarantine recommendations for the public, and is revising the CDC website to reflect these changes. These recommendations do not apply to healthcare personnel and do not supersede state, local, tribal, or territorial laws, rules, and regulations."     See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220109060804/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/contact-tracing.html
column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals.    The July 29th order from Biden still stands, ordering federal workers to be vaccinated or subject themselves to constant masking and frequent testing.     Given that the public transit policy affects more people and is stricter, this is now coded as a 2G - Universal. column32: “The Pritzker Administration, in partnership with the Illinois Department of Commerce and Economic Opportunity (DCEO), is leveraging federal ARPA funds to help Illinois families access and afford home energy assistance and other essential services during COVID-19. Building on the State’s Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) and the Community Services Block Grant (CSBG) program, the State’s Fiscal Year 2022 (FY 22) budget authorizes an expansion of the LIHEAP and CSBG programs for eligible Illinoisans seeking assistance to cover costs of utility bills, rent, temporary shelter, food, and other household necessities.”    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220118040236/https://www2.illinois.gov/dceo/CommunityServices/HomeWeatherization/CommunityActionAgencies/Pages/HelpIllinoisFamilies.aspx

column52: All residents age 8 and older have been required to wear face coverings in most public settings since July 27 under Gov.  Eric J. Holcomb’s Executive Order 20-37, which was renewed with Executive Order 20-48. Note that children younger  than 2 years old should not wear a face covering due to the risk of suffocation, according to the Centers for Disease  Control and Prevention (CDC). It recommends that children 2-8 wear face coverings.  Other exceptions outlined to the face covering requirement in the executive order include people with disabilities, while  drinking, eating, exercising and for medical purposes. Individuals who cannot wear a mask for health reasons should  consider alternatives, such as face shields.  The executive order requires face coverings for anyone 8 years and older in:  • Public indoor spaces and commercial entities  • Public outdoor spaces when it’s impossible to socially distance from people not in your household  • Public transportation or other vehicle services such as a taxi or ride-share    For more information, see archive:   https://archive.ph/aNtjM
column55: Vaccines in Indiana are universally available. The Pfizer vaccine is available for those 5 years old and up. The Pfizer vaccine booster shot is now available for those aged 12-15.     For more information, see archive:   https://archive.ph/c1g8N

column34: The Kansas Emergency Rental Assistance (KERA) program provides rent, utility, and internet assistance to households experiencing financial hardship as a result of the COVID pandemic. Landlords and tenants apply via a joint online process. If the application is approved, the landlord or service provider receives funds directly from KERA and applies KERA funds to the applicant’s account. Approved applicants are eligible for up to 12 months of assistance.    For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/xsXYB

column9: As of January 17, 2022, there is no recommendation to close schools.  "CDC and KDHE  recommend universal  indoor  masking  for  all  teachers,  staff,  students,  and visitors  (age 2  and older)  to K-12  schools,  regardless  of  vaccination status.   o  Masks should be  worn by  all  individuals  (age  2  and older)  on all  forms  of  public transportation including school  buses  regardless  of  vaccination status. •  Schools  should strive to  maintain at  least  3  feet  of  physical  distance between students  within classrooms;  however,  the inability  to implement  physical  distancing  within schools  should not  be  a barrier  to  keeping all  students  learning in-person.  When  it  is  not  possible to maintain at  least  3  feet  of  physical  distancing,  it  is  especially  important  to  layer  all  prevention strategies  including  vaccination,  testing,  masking  and  good personal  hygiene."    https://archive.ph/knlaF
column12: As of January 17, 2022, there is no recommendation to close workplaces. Protect Your Team  Monitor employees temperatures and symptoms regularly. Issue or approve face coverings. Be mindful of spaces where 6 feet of distance can’t be maintained. Disinfect workspaces at the beginning and end of each shift/work day. These include 6ft social distancing for the unvaccinated, masking in vehicles, regular cleaning, provision for handwashing, installation of 'sneeze-guards', and quarantine for infected employees.  Louisiana Department of Health recommends working from home. column45: Massachusetts's Community Tracing Collaborative program ended in December 2021. The program was created "to help support local health departments from every community in their contact tracing work. The program focuses on reaching out to people who have tested positive for COVID-19 and the contacts they have been close to, making sure they have the support they need to isolate or quarantine."    The Boston Globe reports there are no more state-funded workers to help track new infections, so local health departments have been advised by the state to only do contact tracing for COVID-19 cases in group settings where infections are more likely to spread rapidly. That includes health care facilities, homeless shelters, nursing homes, daycare centers and schools. However, MassNotify, a smartphone tool that can notify you "if another user you’ve been near tests positive for COVID-19 within a 14-day period." Because the tool allows for limited contact tracing and not all identified cases, this policy is coded as a 1.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050255/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-community-tracing-collaborative-ctc  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050524/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/enable-massnotify-on-your-smartphone

column9: Schools still remain open with significant alterations. No changes.     On October 26, 2021 the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE) and Elementary and Secondary Education Commissioner Jeffrey C. Riley announced "that he will extend the mask requirement in all K-12 public schools through at least January 15, 2022." However, "school officials will continue to be able to lift the mask requirement if they can demonstrate that at least 80 percent of all students and staff in a school building are vaccinated after submitting documentation to DESE." On January 5, 2022 it was announced that "the Department distributed KN95 masks to districts last week." Schools have been sporadically closing for a few days and/or delaying opening hours due to staffing shortage either from testing positive for COVID or for other personal reasons. However, since this is not reflected in either city or state policy, this is still coded as 1G.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044614/https://mailchi.mp/doe.mass.edu/press-release-i6d5p52m94  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044626/https://mailchi.mp/doe.mass.edu/commissioners-weekly-update-1-3-22-covid-19-updates-leveraging-technology-upcoming-learnlaunch-workshops-96612  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044619/https://www.doe.mass.edu/covid19/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044622/https://www.doe.mass.edu/commissioner/updates.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044814/https://www.wcvb.com/article-recommendation/leftrail?model=cream&articles=38675422%2C38672090%2C38679851%2C38675420%2C38678528%2C38668719%2C38674178%2C38667834%2C38679603%2C38670674%2C38657671%2C38678789%2C38676561%2C38665531%2C38674892&version=bayesian_net_10_30_05_30_10_03  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106044824/https://www.masslive.com/weather/2022/01/school-closings-and-delays-for-monday-jan-3.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106045020/https://docs.google.com/document/d/1T29b10etWbOwZGcBWnmTdfsk7i2eIerouPp1gkttwdw/edit

column32: The Emergency Paid Sick Leave program is now set to expire April 1, 2022.  Under the law, employees are permitted to take paid sick leave for certain reasons, including to address their own COVID-19-related health issues, obtain or recover from a COVID-19 vaccination, or to care for a family member affected by COVID-19. The extension expands the reasons for which employees can use Emergency Paid Sick Leave to care for a family member. The original law allowed employees to take leave to care for a family member who must self-isolate or quarantine for reasons related to COVID-19 or who seeks medical diagnosis, care, or treatment for COVID-19. Under the extension, employees may now also use leave to care for a family member who needs to obtain or recover from a COVID-19 vaccine. Employees are eligible to receive up to a total of $850 in Emergency Paid Sick Leave benefits.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106045638/https://www.jdsupra.com/legalnews/massachusetts-governor-signs-extension-6696925/    If you’re out of work and able to work, you may be eligible for temporary income called unemployment insurance (UI). If you qualify, you receive weekly payments to help cover your living expenses while you search for new employment. The amount you receive is based on what you were paid in the last year. The UI program for Massachusetts is managed by the Department of Unemployment Assistance (DUA).  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106045734/https://www.mass.gov/unemployment-insurance-ui-for-workers    Transitional Aid to Families with Dependent Children (TAFDC) and Emergency Aid to the Elderly, Disabled and Children (EAEDC) are economic assistance (cash benefit) programs that help individuals and families explore opportunities, improve their finances, and reach their goals.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106045728/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/financial-assistance-during-the-covid-19-crisis
column34: Between November 15, 2021 and March 15, 2022 "your electric or gas company cannot shut off your service ... without written approval from the Department of Public Utilities (DPU)" if all residents of your household are 65 years or older, someone at home is critically ill, or there is an infant under 12 months at home. If you want to remain in your current home but owe past due rent, you may apply directly to the Emergency Rental Assistance Program for help. To qualify for rental assistance in Massachusetts, you must have an income no more than 80 percent of the area median income (AMI), and you must be able to prove a financial hardship related to COVID-19 and be at risk of homelessness or housing instability.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050101/https://www.mass.gov/service-details/when-am-i-protected-from-having-my-utilities-shut-off  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050106/https://www.randolph-ma.gov/home/news/winter-utility-assistance
column41: No change. The archived source below provides educational materials for everyone.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050230/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/stop-covid-19-vaccine-education-and-outreach-materials
column43: Testing remains widely available. "The Commonwealth has launched free drive-through Express COVID-19 Testing Sites in partnership with Project Beacon. The sites are open to all Massachusetts residents."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220106043003/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/find-a-covid-19-test  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050225/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-testing-guidance
column45: Massachusetts's Community Tracing Collaborative program ended in December 2021. The program was created "to help support local health departments from every community in their contact tracing work. The program focuses on reaching out to people who have tested positive for COVID-19 and the contacts they have been close to, making sure they have the support they need to isolate or quarantine."    The Boston Globe reports there are no more state-funded workers to help track new infections, so local health departments have been advised by the state to only do contact tracing for COVID-19 cases in group settings where infections are more likely to spread rapidly. That includes health care facilities, homeless shelters, nursing homes, daycare centers and schools. However, MassNotify, a smartphone tool that can notify you "if another user you’ve been near tests positive for COVID-19 within a 14-day period." Because the tool allows for limited contact tracing and not all identified cases, this policy is coded as a 1.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050255/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-community-tracing-collaborative-ctc  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050524/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/enable-massnotify-on-your-smartphone
column52: No change. Since August 27, 2021 "face masks are required in all indoor public settings in the City of Boston." This includes whenever people are "indoors on the premises of a business, club, place of assembly or other place that is open to members of the public, including but not limited to retail establishments, restaurants, bars, performance venues, social clubs, event spaces, and municipal buildings. "Face coverings may be removed when actively eating or drinking. Masks must be worn for all other indoor activities."     Effective May 29, 2021, The state of Massachusetts still has mask requirements for both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals at all times in the following locations, such as public transportation, healthcare facilities, congregate care facilities, emergency shelter programs, correctional facilities, health care and day services, and home health workers. As of December 21, 2021 "the Department of Public Health now advises that all residents, regardless of vaccination status, wear a mask or face covering when indoors (and not in your own home)." However, since the policies of the city of Boston are stricter, this is coded as a 3T.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220106051219/https://www.boston.gov/news/coronavirus-disease-covid-19-boston  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106050946/https://www.boston.gov/news/mayor-janey-announces-indoor-mask-mandate-city-boston  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106051011/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-mask-requirements
column55: The COVID-19 vaccine is free for people ages 5+ who live, work or study in Mass. An ID or insurance is not needed to receive it. People ages 5-17 can get the Pfizer vaccine. People age 18+ can get any vaccine. Everyone age 18+ who received Pfizer or Moderna at least 6 months ago or Johnson & Johnson at least 2 months ago can get any booster.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220106043113/https://www.mass.gov/covid-19-vaccine
column58: No change. Updated January 3, 2022:    - Long Term Care Facilities (LTCF) must have a way to assess visitors for COVID symptoms and visitors are must wear masks.   - "While not recommended, residents who are in isolation or quarantine can still receive visitors."   - "Long-term care facilities should ensure all staff are using appropriate PPE when they are interacting with residents and in alignment with DPH and CDC guidance."  - "In addition to the circumstance-specific testing requirements described above in this memo, long-term care facilities are required to perform weekly surveillance testing of all staff and outbreak testing of residents and staff as soon as possible."  - On August 4th, 2021, the Baker-Polito Administration announced a requirement that all nursing home staff demonstrate that they have received and are maintaining vaccination to protect against COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220106052941/https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-public-health-guidance-and-directives

column27: Update December 21st (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111065215/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html

column27: Update December 21st (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Recommends that both vaccinated and unvaccinated wear masks throughout travel:    "Delay travel until you are fully vaccinated. Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. CDC recommends you get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose if you are eligible. People who are not fully vaccinated should follow additional recommendations before, during, and after travel."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111060625/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html
column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111065215/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html

column43: Fully vaccinated individuals should get tested if they:  -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.  -Have had close contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. You should get tested within 3-5 days after exposure.  -Are traveling internationally and returning to the United States. Fully vaccinated international travelers are required to get tested three days before travel by air into the U.S. and should also get tested 3-5 days after their trip.    Unvaccinated individuals should get tested if they:   -Are experiencing symptoms of COVID-19. Anyone experiencing symptoms should get tested immediately.   -Have come in contact with someone who has COVID-19, even if they are not experiencing symptoms. If they do not have symptoms, they should wait at least six days after their last known exposure to COVID-19 before they get tested.  -Take part in activities that put them at higher risk for COVID-19 because they cannot physically distance as needed to avoid exposure, such as travel, attending large social or mass gatherings, or being in crowded or poorly ventilated indoor settings.    If available through an employer or another organization, unvaccinated individuals can be part of a program where they get tested regularly for COVID-19.    See Archive:  https://archive.vn/fUjTw

column52: Douglas County Health Director "signed a public health order for a mask mandate in the City of Omaha" which went into effect at 12:01 a.m. January 12 and "will remain until positive case counts for the City of Omaha are below 200 persons per 100,000 on seven (7) days total and hospital capacity is maintained at or below 85% for seven (7) consecutive days unless renewed, extended or terminated by subsequent order".  The Mayor of Omaha does not agree with the order but recognizes that the Health Director has the authority to do so.    https://archive.vn/bmGqp  https://archive.ph/xHMwX

Douglas County's Health Director issued a mask mandate order effective Jan 12th and on Jan 13th Nebraska's Governor announced that he supports Nebraska's Attorney General’s "legal action to stop unapproved Douglas County Mask Mandate".    https://archive.ph/lLw4f

Lincoln Mayor and Lincoln-Lancaster Count Health Department Director announced that the city of Lincoln will reinstate its indoor mask mandate which goes into effect on "Saturday, Jan. 15, and extend to Friday, Feb. 11" and "applies to everyone ages 2 and older regardless of vaccination status".     https://archive.ph/XMjOi

column24: New Hampshire stay at home requirements have been lifted, in light of the COVID best practices being released   https://web.archive.org/web/20211217005928/https://www.covidguidance.nh.gov/sites/g/files/ehbemt381/files/inline-documents/sonh/universal-best-practices.pdf
column27: Update December 21st (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Recommends that both vaccinated and unvaccinated wear masks throughout travel:    "Delay travel until you are fully vaccinated. Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. CDC recommends you get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose if you are eligible. People who are not fully vaccinated should follow additional recommendations before, during, and after travel."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220104024256/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html
column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220103124420/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html
column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals.    The July 29th order from Biden still stands, ordering federal workers to be vaccinated or subject themselves to constant masking and frequent testing.     Given that the public transit policy affects more people and is stricter, this is now coded as a 2G - Universal. column34: The state of New Jersey continues to offer rental assistance:  "Opening March 22, 2021, the COVID-19 Emergency Rental Assistance Program Phase II (CVERAP Phase II) will provide rental arrears and temporary rental assistance to low- and moderate-income households that have had a substantial reduction in income, have qualified for unemployment benefits, incurred significant costs, or experienced a financial hardship due, directly, or indirectly, to the COVID-19 pandemic. Nan McKay & Associates has been authorized by the New Jersey Department of Community Affairs to assist in the administration of CVERAP Phase II and to communicate with applicants and landlords."     and has an eviction moratorium:   "If you live in a New Jersey household with income below 120% of your county's Area Median Income, you are permanently protected from eviction or removal at any time for nonpayment of rent, habitual late payment of rent, or failure to accept a rent increase that accrued from March 1, 2020 to August 31, 2021.    Depending on your household's income level and specific circumstances, you may also be eligible for protection from eviction or removal through December 31, 2021, and other assistance and services. These protections are not affected by the Supreme Court's decision on the CDC's eviction moratorium."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20211115090356/https://www.nj.gov/dca/cverap2.shtml    https://web.archive.org/web/20211115143227/https://covid19.nj.gov/pages/renter

column58: The department of health of New Jersey continues to mandate protections for the elderly at long term care facilities:     "If both the visitor and the resident are fully vaccinated, residents and their visitors may choose to have close contact including touching and removing their facemasks if they are alone in the resident's room or the designated visitation room.    Fully vaccinated residents may choose to have close contact including touching with their unvaccinated visitor, however they both must wear well-fitting face masks    Indoor visitation at long-term care facilities in regions where the COVID-19 Activity Level Index (CALI score) is high or very high and less than 70% of the residents of the facility are fully vaccinated, should be limited for unvaccinated or partially vaccinated residents.    Indoor visitation of unvaccinated residents can take place regardless of CALI score if 70% of the residents in the facility are vaccinated.    Indoor compassionate care, essential caregiver, and end-of-life visitation and outdoor visitation can be permitted even when indoor visitation is otherwise restricted because of the facility's status.    Indoor visitation should be limited for residents under quarantine, whether vaccinated or unvaccinated, until they have met criteria for release from quarantine.    In addition, indoor visitation should also be limited for residents with confirmed COVID-19 infection, whether vaccinated or unvaccinated, until they have met the criteria to discontinue precautions.    When a new case of COVID-19 among residents or staff is identified, a facility should immediately begin testing and suspend visitation (except as required under federal disability rights law and Department guidance/directives) until at least one round of facility-wide testing is completed."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20211117092350/https://covid19.nj.gov/faqs/nj-information/reopening-guidance-and-restrictions/can-i-visit-a-nursing-home-or-long-term-care-facility-what-are-the-safety-protocols

column21: As published by NJ transit report:  "NJ TRANSIT's operating units have in place clear protocols and procedures for the cleaning and disinfection of rolling stock, vehicles and public facilities. Our Frequently Asked Questions provide answers to your questions about our ongoing response to COVID-19.    NJ TRANSIT has enhanced its cleaning efforts to include disinfecting vehicles every 24 hours. Hard surface cleaning and disinfecting typically includes handholds, arm rests, seating areas and restrooms.    Our enhanced cleaning regimen in stations includes additional disinfecting of frequent customer touchpoints such as ticket vending machines, handrails, and door handles. In major stations and terminals, this occurs once every shift.    The cleaning agents used in this effort are deemed effective for these purposes and contain anti-viral components such as bleach/water mixes and other disinfectant sprays. Areas regularly cleaned include are doors, door knobs, windows, benches, partitions, trash cans, elevators, escalators, handrails, ledges, all restrooms and floor surfaces and all floor mats.    Customers must use trash receptacles to discard used face coverings and gloves in NJ TRANSIT stations or on vehicles. It's not just litter--it's a matter of public health."   Coded 0 since public transport is still on operation.    See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/*/https://www.njtransit.com/covid19

column45: As of January 10, 2022, limited Contact Tracing remains in place.   There is a free mobile phone app called COVID Trace, which was developed by the Nevada Department of Health and Human Services that uses a technology called the Exposure Notifications System from Google and Apple.  The app exchanges anonymous information with other phones in the vicinity and can notify when the user has been in contact with someone who has tested positive for COVID-19.  Health care providers and laboratories are required by Nevada state law (NAC441A.230 and NAC441A.235) to notify the Health District when someone tests positive or might have COVID-19.  People who have COVID-19 are required to give the Health District the name and contact information of everyone they had close contact with during a certain time period.  There are two ways the Health District gets in touch with people who have COVID-19:  1. A public health worker calls the person.  2. The Health District sends the person who has COVID-19 an automated email or text message with a link to an online portal.  There is no evidence showing the extent of this happening in every Health District in Nevada.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211111043112/https://nvhealthresponse.nv.gov/covidtrace/
column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals. column9: Latest bulletin:   As we begin the new year, school leaders are requesting updated COVID-19 guidance, particularly to changes that have occurred to the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) close contact and quarantine practices.    At this time, schools should follow the most recent PA Department of Health (DOH) Health Alert (PA-HAN) on Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population that was released last Thursday. (615 - 12/30/2021 - UPD - UPDATE: Isolation and Quarantine Periods for COVID-19 for the General Population (PDF))    As with previous updates in guidance, schools are expected to follow the new community guidelines. The CDC has indicated that there will be additional guidance for more specific settings, including schools, released in the near future. DOH will review and update the community guidance in the PA-HAN accordingly if and when CDC makes any further adjustments. Please note that this is a very fluid situation. We appreciate your patience as we work through these changes together.    https://archive.vn/pEyJ8    Two southeastern Pennsylvania school districts announces school closures due to the coronavirus on the heels of their winter breaks.  The Upper Darby and Lower Merion school districts closed schools Monday as case counts rise.  In Lower Merion: If district schools have adequate staffing, in-person learning will resume Tuesday.  Students will also have the option to learn virtually through Jan. 14.  https://archive.vn/UWo4W
column43: The Wolf Administration today announced the launch of a new, free COVID-19 testing site in Delaware County and highlighted the efforts taking place to support Pennsylvanians and community partners on COVID-19 testing.    “To be clear, the best way for Pennsylvanians to protect themselves and vulnerable populations and prevent hospitalization from COVID-19 is for eligible individuals to get vaccinated and boosted,” said Gov. Tom Wolf. “We know that COVID-19 tests are also an important tool to help prevent the spread of this contagious disease, especially as we enter cold and flu season and symptoms for cold, flu and COVID-19 may seem similar. My administration is collaborating with health systems, communities, school districts and the private sector to support their current needs and incentivize the public to get tested before engaging with the public.”     https://archive.vn/Tsvsr
column55: Today, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration amended the emergency use authorization (EUA) for the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine to:  Expand the use of a single booster dose to include use in individuals 12 through 15 years of age.  Shorten the time between the completion of primary vaccination of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine and a booster dose to at least five months.  Allow for a third primary series dose for certain immunocompromised children 5 through 11 years of age.    (No PA specific information has been found, but this is likely to be adopted)    https://archive.vn/ziG8s

column9: If a school is experiencing an outbreak or a rise in cases, the school can contact DOH or their local CMHD if additional guidance on outbreak response is needed. To preserve safe in-person learning to the greatest extent possible, DOH staff will work with schools to determine if a closure is necessary and if so, the appropriate closure length, with a maximum 14-day recommendation for full incubation period.    A maximum 14-day suspension of in-person learning may be recommended by DOH if the following criteria are met:        5% of students/staff confirmed cases in a 14-day window:          Small school (<500 staff & students): 25 case threshold          Medium school (500-900 staff & students): 25-45 case threshold          Large school (900+ staff & students): 45+ case threshold    OR        Three simultaneous classroom and/or core group outbreaks when:          Contact tracing cannot adequately identify close contacts or be completed in a timely manner; and          Other mitigation strategies such as physical distancing or universal masking are not being implemented or adhered to.   https://web.archive.org/web/20211215210556/https://www.education.pa.gov/Schools/safeschools/emergencyplanning/COVID-19/Pages/default.aspx

column9: As of January 17, there is no state-wide mandate to close schools. However, a number of schools in Rhode Island are moving to remote learning amid the surge of COVID-19 in the state and related staffing concerns. For example, Burrillville schools, Esek Hopkins Middle School in Providence, Barrington High School, Coventry High School, and Ponaganset High School all moved to remote learning at the start of January. column41: As of January 17, the Rhode Island Department of Health is still operating a co-ordinated public health campaign.     Source:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220117172038/https://covid.ri.gov/
column43: As of January 17, testing is available for anyone symptomatic, close contacts and people who work in health or congregate settings. column9: South Carolina recommends "Layered Prevention Strategies to Reduce Transmission of COVID-19 in Schools", as published in their COVID-19 GUIDANCE FOR K-12 SCHOOLS document in January 2022.   These include  1. Vaccination  2. Mask use  3. Physical distancing  4. Contact tracing, in combination with isolation and quarantine  5. Staying home when sick and getting tested  6.
