column9: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, K-12 schools remain open in Tennessee. However, at least 31 school districts were closed Thursday, January 20, 2022 and Friday, January 21, 2022 due to staffing issues. Staffing issues are due to a surge of COVID-19 cases among school staff. column12: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there is no statewide mandate regarding workplace closing. The Tennessee Center for Industrial Services has COVID-19 workplace guidance such as, separate sick employees, clean work areas, and tell your team about possible COVID-19 exposure.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105063159/https://www.cis.tennessee.edu/covid-19-resource-dashboard/covid-19-protecting-your-workforce
column15: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there are no requirements for the cancellation of public events.     Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220119031024/https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov/community-guidance.html
column18: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there are no restrictions on gatherings.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220119031024/https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov/community-guidance.html
column21: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there are no requirements for closing public transport. Public Transportation is available in every county in Tennessee, with a wide range of services. Tennessee is following the federal mask requirements for public transport.     Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120211756/https://www.tn.gov/tdot/multimodal-transportation-resources/office-of-public-transportation/public-transit-services1.html   https://web.archive.org/web/20220120211829/https://www.transportation.gov/mask-up/tool-kit
column24: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there are no stay at home requirements in place. Since April 30, 2021, there have been no stay at home requirements.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105064415/https://sos.tn.gov/publications/services/executive-orders-governor-bill-lee
column32: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, income support policies have not changed. Tennessee offers income support through an emergency cash assistance program for people who have lost their job as a result of the pandemic that can be combined with unemployment benefits.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105081320/https://www.tn.gov/humanservices/news/2020/3/25/financial-aid-available-for-certain-families-that-lost-employment-due-to-covid-19.html
column34: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, the COVID-19 Rent Relief Program is still in place, offering support for renters who are or have been struggling to pay rent, utilities, or other home energy costs due to loss of wages/income as a result of the pandemic. This program is available for every county in Tennessee except for the following areas; Davidson County, Knox County, Memphis/Shelby County, and Rutherford County. Citizens in these counties will have to contact their local government.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105065657/https://thda.org/help-for-renters-section-8/covidrentrelief
column41: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, there is still a public health campaign (mostly online and social media) in Tennessee. The website is primarily focused on the COVID-19 vaccination campaign.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120212917/https://www.tn.gov/health/cedep/ncov.html
column43: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, health officials in Tennessee recommend that “If you have any doubts whatsoever about your exposure to COVID-19, please get a test.” There are many testing sites in every county for TN residents.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105070108/https://covid19.tn.gov/prevention/what-to-do-if-exposed/
column45: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, the following is guidance on contact tracing from the Tennessee Department of Health:  "You may receive a call or text from public health if you have been in close contact with someone with  COVID-19. They will explain quarantine guidance and answer any questions you have. If you have any  additional questions, contact your local health department."    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105070227/https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/documents/cedep/novel-coronavirus/CaseGuidance.pdf
column55: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, COVID-19 Vaccines are now widely available to all Tennesseans 5+ in all 95 counties across our state. No appointment necessary. Walk-in options are available at all health departments.    Archived link:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120213913/https://covid19.tn.gov/covid-19-vaccines/availability/
column58: No policy change. As of January 20, 2022, the Tennessee Department of Health has guidance in place to protect residents of long-term care facilities, including contact tracing, screening, and testing. There is also a push to distribute booster shots at LTCFs. State-specific visitation restrictions in Tennessee have ended since Feb. 28, 2021.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120214031/https://www.tn.gov/health/health-professionals/hcf-main/health-care-facilities-covid-19-measures-information-page/long-term-care-taskforce/long-term-care-facility-resources.html   https://web.archive.org/web/20220105071722/https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/documents/cedep/novel-coronavirus/datasets/LTCF-Visitation-Overview.pdf

column27: Update December 21st (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Recommends that both vaccinated and unvaccinated wear masks throughout travel:    "Delay travel until you are fully vaccinated. Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. CDC recommends you get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose if you are eligible. People who are not fully vaccinated should follow additional recommendations before, during, and after travel."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111060625/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html
column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111065215/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html
column52: On August 27th, the CDC updated guidance for wearing masks in public transit settings. This is directed at both vaccinated and unvaccinated individuals.    The July 29th order from Biden still stands, ordering federal workers to be vaccinated or subject themselves to constant masking and frequent testing.     Given that the public transit policy affects more people and is stricter, this is now coded as a 2G - Universal.     See archive:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101145401/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/masks.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fprevent-getting-sick%2Fdiy-cloth-face-coverings.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111194558/https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/masks/mask-travel-guidance.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20220111035057/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/face-masks-public-transportation.html

column9: Schools must verify student and staff vaccinations. "Fully vaccinated students and staff who do not have symptoms do not have to quarantine when exposed to COVID-19 and may not require COVID-19 testing as indicated below. Further, while universal masking is required of all students and staff now, there is the possibility in the future that fully vaccinated people may no longer be required to wear masks indoors."    Correct use of cloth face coverings or masks helps prevent the spread of COVID-19 and is required when indoors at K-12 facilities for all school personnel, students, and visitors. There are specific exceptions based on age, development, or disability.    The CDC’s order requiring masks on public transportation, regardless of vaccination status, applies to school buses and transportation. Passengers and drivers are required to wear a mask on school buses.     All school personnel, volunteers, visitors, and students must wear cloth face coverings, or an acceptable alternative (e.g., surgical mask or clear face shield with a drape), at school when indoors in accordance with the Secretary of Health’s Mask Order.    Schools should maintain physical distance of three feet or more between students in classroom settings to the degree possible and reasonable, that allows for full-time, in-person learning for all students.     This guidance has been updated on december 17, 2021; In response to recent sports-related outbreaks, the testing requirements for high-risk  sporting activities has been updated to require screening testing of all athletes, coaches, trainers and supporting personnel, regardless of vaccination status.    For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/RXAD4

column43: No change. Testing is available to all, although it is recommended that one "seek testing if you have symptoms of COVID-19 or have been in close contact with someone who may be positive for COVID-19. You should get tested immediately if having symptoms, or 3-5 days after suspected exposure, even if you don’t experience any symptoms."  There are no out of pocket cost for tests performed at county or state-supported test sites. Many tests, particularly for people experiencing symptoms, can be billed to insurance or subsidized by the Department of Health.    For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/XmyTv
column45: No change. Contact tracing starts with a person who tested positive for COVID-19. This person will be advised to stay home except to get medical care until they are no longer contagious. A trained interviewer will reach out to the person who has tested positive and ask for the contact information of close contacts (A close contact is a person who has been within 6 feet, for 15 minutes or more, of someone who tested positive for COVID-19). Next, the interviewer will reach out to the contacts to let them know they have been exposed. Contacts stay home to watch for symptoms for 14 days after they were exposed.     For more information, see:   https://archive.ph/0kiER
column52: No changes. Because of a steep increase in disease transmission in Washington, the Secretary of Health is requiring that everyone five years of age and older wear a mask in public indoor settings and at large, outdoor events with 500 or more attendees. There are some exceptions to the mask requirement, including:  > Children under five years of age. However, children age two to four years old can wear a mask under close adult supervision.   > People with a medical or mental health condition or disability that prevents them from wearing a mask.   > Anyone who is working alone, regardless of vaccination status.  > Verified fully vaccinated workers who are working in an area not accessible to the public.   > Athletes who play indoor sports and who are actively engaged in competition or practice (masks are still required on sidelines and in team meetings).   > Small indoor private gatherings and outdoor events with fewer than 500 people, where physical distancing is possible.     For more information, please see:   https://archive.ph/Rv2ee
column55: Vaccines are available for those 5 years old or older. There are no costs to the individual who is getting vaccinated. It is also not necessary to be a U.S citizen to get vaccinated.     For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/9OX5D
column58: No changes. Governor Jay Inslee issued Proclamation 20-46.3 (pdf) April 8, 2021, amending Proclamation 20-05 (pdf), which prevents all employers, public or private, from failing to provide accommodation to high-risk employees, as defined by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), that protects them from risk of exposure to the COVID-19 disease on the job. This ensures that elderly workers can be protected.     Regarding indoor visitation in nursing homes and long term care facilities the safest practice is for patients and visitors to wear source control and physically distance, particularly if either of them are at risk for severe disease or are unvaccinated. If the patient and all their visitor(s) are fully vaccinated, they can choose not to wear source control and to have physical contact. Visitors should wear source control when around other residents or HCP, regardless of vaccination status.    For more information, visit:   https://archive.ph/c5qVl

column58: As of 17 January 2022,  There are no changes.    "Based on guidance from the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), the Department of Health Services (DHS) recommends the following actions in accordance with Wis. Stat. chs. 50 and 252, Wis. Admin. Code chs. DHS 132, DHS 134, and DHS 145. CMS and CDC continue to provide guidance for nursing homes and other long-term care facilities.  Facilities are encouraged to routinely check the CMS and CDC websites for additional guidance. In addition to reading and understanding the guidance offered here, it is important to review the information highlighted in the hyperlinks and in the Resources section. Facilities are also encouraged to use the COVID-19 Provider Self-Assessment Worksheet, F-02669 (Word) as a tool to guide their overall preparedness."    https://archive.vn/FyEUu

column29: On December 31st, the Biden administration lifted the previous ban of a list of countries and implemented rules for both vaccinated and unvaccinated persons:     "You must be fully vaccinated to travel to the United States by plane if you are a non-U.S. citizen, non-U.S. immigrant (not a U.S. citizen, U.S. national, lawful permanent resident, or traveling to the United States on an immigrant visa). Only limited exceptions apply...    all air passengers, regardless of vaccination status, must show a negative COVID-19 test taken no more than 1 day before travel to the United States."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220111065215/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/noncitizens-US-air-travel.html

column27: Update December 21st (no change in stringency level), the CDC recommends those that are unvaccinated to delay travel until fully vaccinated and recommends testing before and after travel (if travelling while unvaccinated). Recommends that both vaccinated and unvaccinated wear masks throughout travel:    "Delay travel until you are fully vaccinated. Getting vaccinated is still the best way to protect yourself from severe disease, slow the spread of COVID-19, and reduce the number of new variants. CDC recommends you get a COVID-19 vaccine booster dose if you are eligible. People who are not fully vaccinated should follow additional recommendations before, during, and after travel."    See archive:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220104024256/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html

column12: As of Jan. 4, flexible control measures are in place across Venezuela as part of the country's COVID-19 response program. The government has temporarily ended its long-standing "7+7" program, under which a series of strict restrictions alternated with flexible measures weekly. The flexible measures will remain indefinitely; however, authorities have said they may reimpose the plan if infections increase.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220112010041/https://crisis24.garda.com/insights-intelligence/intelligence/risk-alerts/wip10011867871/venezuela-authorities-maintain-flexible-covid-19-related-measures-as-of-jan-4-update-70
column15: Under the general flexible restrictions, authorities allow most businesses and facilities, including lodging establishments, beaches, private clubs, theme parks, restaurants, cafes, public transport, banks, and financial services, healthcare centers, and places of worship, among numerous others, to operate.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220112010041/https://crisis24.garda.com/insights-intelligence/intelligence/risk-alerts/wip10011867871/venezuela-authorities-maintain-flexible-covid-19-related-measures-as-of-jan-4-update-70

column27: Local and regional governments could impose additional restrictions, including limiting intercity or interstate vehicular travel. Enhanced measures are likely in border areas.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220112010041/https://crisis24.garda.com/insights-intelligence/intelligence/risk-alerts/wip10011867871/venezuela-authorities-maintain-flexible-covid-19-related-measures-as-of-jan-4-update-70
column29: Multiple international flights remain banned until further notice. Authorities only allow authorized commercial international flights to and from Bolivia, Dominican Republic, Mexico, Panama, Russia, and Turkey. Cargo, emergency, and humanitarian flights are exempt from the ban.    All passengers entering Venezuela must present a negative result from a COVID-19 test taken no more than 48 hours before arrival. Any person entering the country may have to undergo additional testing upon arrival and could be subject to quarantine protocols.    All measures are subject to amendment at short notice. Authorities could tighten restrictions in any location at any time if confirmed case numbers increase significantly.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220112010041/https://crisis24.garda.com/insights-intelligence/intelligence/risk-alerts/wip10011867871/venezuela-authorities-maintain-flexible-covid-19-related-measures-as-of-jan-4-update-70
